# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agriculture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] ABC-Clio provides service to fifteen different online databases which contain over one million online textbooks.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The company consults academic leaders in the fields they cover in order to provide authority for their reference titles.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The headquarters are located in Santa Barbara, California.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] ABC-Clio was founded in 1955 as a privately held corporation by Eric Boehm with its first publication, *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The name represents the company's two original divisions when it incorporated in 1969: ABC stands for American Bibliographical Center and Clio Press is named after Clio, the muse of history from ancient Greek mythology.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] According to Boehm, he had always been interested in history so when he noticed that there were not many good historical abstracting services available, he started publishing the *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] During the 1960s, a sister bibliographic and abstract publication on American history was added, *America: History and Life*, which was considered an award-winning title.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The company entered into digital publishing with electronic data in the 1960s and in 1975, it published its first online database called *DIALOG*.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] During the 1980s, ABC-Clio expanded into providing primary reference books such as encyclopedias and dictionaries and stopped publishing bibliographic books.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In the 1990s, ABC-Clio began to provide access to its humanities database on CD-ROM.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The *Exegy Current Events* CD-ROM was named "Best Disc of the Year" by Library Journal.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 1998, ABC-Clio provided electronic access to *America: History and Life*.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] By the 2000s, one of the company's most popular products had become online databases for researching many topics in the field of the humanities.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 2001, ABC-Clio began to publish eBooks, initially providing 150 different titles to schools and libraries.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The company's reference books had won numerous awards, and the company started a series of subject-related online databases for secondary school use.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 2004, the company acquired the quarterly historical journal, *Journal of the West*, which has been published since 1962.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 1996, ABC-Clio merged with an electronic publishing company, Intellimation, which also produced educational software.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The merger brought Becky Snyder, who by 2009 had become ABC-Clio's president, from Intellimation.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 2007, it sold two databases – *Historical Abstracts* and *America: History and Life* – to EBSCO Publishing; in addition, the companies also agreed a partnership through which nine additional ABC-Clio databases would be distributed through EBSCO Publishing.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing acquired ABC-Clio for US$22.9 million (equivalent to $26.1 million in 2024).
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 2008, ABC-Clio acquired the Greenwood Publishing Group from Houghton Mifflin Harcourt.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The deal gave ABC-Clio a "perpetual license" to use the imprints of Greenwood Press and publish all of its titles.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] Acquiring the publishing group gave ABC-Clio access to Greenwood Press, Praeger Publishers, Praeger Security International, and Libraries Unlimited.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] Greenwood focuses on publishing full-text reference works which are authoritative on various topics.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] Libraries Unlimited came to ABC-Clio as part of a deal with Greenwood Press.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 2012, Kathyrn Suárez was named publisher for this division, which focuses on publishing for librarians and information professionals.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] ABC-Clio databases are provided under the umbrella of ABC-Clio Solutions.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] There are fifteen different databases providing access to different subject areas.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] ABC-Clio Solutions provides digital curriculum with multimedia content, text-to-speech features, translation tools which covers various topics relating to history and the humanities.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] After ABC-Clio acquired Greenwood Press's databases, they revamped the look and feel of their interface in order to provide common access through the ABC-Clio interface.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] ABC-Clio also provided the ability to search across multiple databases through one search, also providing options for narrowing the search after revamping their interface.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] The new interface is considered user-friendly and provides access to personalized features.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] Originally publishing books by disillusioned former Communists who had fled from behind the Iron Curtain, the publishing house became known for publishing "scholarly and professional books" in the subject areas of social sciences and the humanities.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 1966, Praeger sold his firm to William B.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] Benton, an American senator and publisher and the chairman of *Encyclopaedia Britannica*.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] In 1976, it was sold to CBS, which had shortened the name to Praeger Publishing before selling it to Greenwood Press, Inc., in 1986.
[src:agriculture/abc-clio] When the renamed Greenwood Publishing Group (GPG) was acquired by ABC-Clio in 2009, Praeger Publishing became a standalone imprint of ABC-Clio, and remained such when, in December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing bought ABC-Clio.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The fundamental principle of aeroponic growing entails suspending plants in a closed or semi-closed environment whilst spraying their dangling roots and lower stems with a nutrient-rich water solution in an atomized or sprayed form.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The upper portion of the plant, including the leaves and crown, referred to as the canopy, extends above.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The plant support structure keeps the roots separated.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] To minimize labor and expenses, closed-cell foam is often compressed around the lower stem and inserted into an opening in the aeroponic chamber.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In the case of larger plants, trellising is employed to support the weight of the vegetation and fruits.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The goal is to maintain an environment free from pests and diseases, allowing the plants to thrive and grow faster than those cultivated in a growing medium.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, since most aeroponic environments are not completely sealed off from the outside, pests and diseases can still pose a threat.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Controlled environments facilitate the advancement of plant development, health, growth, flowering, and fruiting for various plant species and cultivars.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Due to the sensitivity of root systems, aeroponics is often combined with conventional hydroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] High-pressure aeroponics refers to the method of delivering nutrients to the roots using mist heads with a size range of 20-50 micrometers.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This is achieved using a high-pressure diaphragm pump operating at around 80 pounds per square inch (550 kPa).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Air cultures maximize air exposure to facilitate optimal plant growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The materials and devices that hold and support aeroponically grown plants must be completely free from disease or pathogens.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] A vital characteristic of a genuine aeroponic culture and apparatus is minimal plant support features.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This design allows maximum airflow around the plant by minimizing contact between the plant and the support structure.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In long-term aeroponic cultivation, it is crucial to ensure that the root systems are unconstrained, allowing unrestricted growth, root expansion, unhindered access to pure water, adequate air exchange, and disease-free conditions.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Adequate oxygen (O2) availability in the rhizosphere (root zone) is essential for promoting healthy plant growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In aeroponics, where plants are grown in an environment of air and micro-droplets of water, almost any plant can thrive and reach maturity with an abundant supply of oxygen, water, and nutrients.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Some growers prefer aeroponic systems over other hydroponic methods, since the increased aeration of the nutrient solution provides greater oxygenation to the plant roots, stimulating growth and aiding in the prevention of pathogen formation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Clean air plays a crucial role in purifying the environment for plants in aeroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Unrestricted access to air is necessary for natural plant growth and successful physiological development.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] If the support structure restricts the plant's natural growth, it can increase the risk of plant damage and subsequent disease formation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Researchers have utilized aeroponics to study the impact of gas composition in the root zone on plant performance.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Soffer and Burger (1988) conducted a study on the effects of dissolved oxygen concentrations in a system they termed "aero-hydroponics," which involved a 3-tier hydro and aero system with distinct zones within the root area.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Their results indicated that dissolved oxygen is crucial for root formation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, they found that in the misted section, where nutrient mist was provided, the number and length of roots were consistently greater compared to the submerged or un-misted sections.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Even at the lowest oxygen concentration tested, the misted section demonstrated successful root development.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics also entails the management of CO2 levels in the system's air, which subsequently impacts the rate of photosynthesis in plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Utilizing artificial lights for growth offers advantages such as increased growth rates and enhanced reliability compared to solar lighting.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This lighting method can be effectively combined with aeroponics to optimize plant growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics offers the advantage of limiting disease transmission since it reduces plant-to-plant contact, and each spray pulse can be kept sterile.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In contrast, diseases can easily spread throughout soil, aggregate, or other growing media, affecting multiple plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Traditional greenhouses often require sterilization of solid media after each crop, and sometimes these media are simply discarded and replaced with fresh, sterile ones.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] One significant benefit of aeroponic technology is the ability to quickly remove a diseased plant from the plant support structure without disrupting or infecting other plants, thanks to the isolated nature of the system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Due to the disease-free environment unique to aeroponics, many plants can be grown at higher densities (plants per square meter) compared to more traditional cultivation methods like hydroponics, soil, and Nutrient Film Technique (NFT).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Commercial aeroponic systems incorporate hardware features that accommodate the expanding root systems of crops.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Researchers have highlighted aeroponics as a valuable, simple, and rapid method for preliminary screening of genotypes for resistance to specific seedling blights or root rots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The isolating nature of aeroponic systems enables researchers to avoid complications encountered when studying these infections in soil cultures.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponic equipment employs sprayers, misters, foggers, or other devices to create a fine mist of solution for delivering nutrients to plant roots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponic systems are typically closed-looped systems designed to provide macro and micro-environments that sustain reliable and consistent air cultures.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Several inventions have been developed to facilitate aeroponic spraying and misting.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The size of the water droplet is critical for root development in an aeroponic environment.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In commercial applications, a 360° hydro-atomizing spray is used, which utilizes air pressure misting to cover large areas of roots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] A variation of the mist technique, known as fogponics, utilizes ultrasonic foggers to mist nutrient solutions in low-pressure aeroponic devices.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Water droplet size plays a vital role in maintaining aeroponic growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Water droplets that are too large can limit the availability of oxygen to the root system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Conversely, excessively fine water droplets generated by ultrasonic misters can lead to excessive root hair growth without developing a lateral root system necessary for sustained growth in an aeroponic system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Mineralization of ultrasonic transducers requires maintenance and presents a potential risk of component failure.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This is also a drawback of metal spray jets and misters.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Restricted access to water can cause plants to lose turgidity and wilt.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] NASA has provided funding for research and development of new advanced materials aimed at improving the reliability and reducing maintenance in aeroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] It has been determined that a high-pressure hydro-atomized mist with micro-droplets ranging from 5 to 50 micrometers is necessary for sustained aeroponic growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] To ensure long-term growth, the mist system must possess significant pressure to effectively penetrate the dense root system(s).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Achieving repeatability is crucial in aeroponics, and this includes maintaining the appropriate hydro-atomized droplet size.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The degradation of the spray caused by mineralization of mist heads hampers the delivery of the water nutrient solution, resulting in an environmental imbalance within the air culture system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] To address this issue, special low-mass polymer materials have been developed and are utilized to prevent mineralization in the next generation of hydro-atomizing misting and spray jets.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These materials help maintain the efficiency and effectiveness of the misting system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The discrete nature of interval and duration aeroponics allows for the measurement of nutrient uptake over time, even under varying conditions.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Barak et al. conducted a study using an aeroponic system to non-destructively measure water and ion uptake rates in cranberries (Barak, Smith et al.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In their research, the team found that by measuring the concentrations and volumes of input and efflux solutions, they could accurately calculate the nutrient uptake rate.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] To validate their findings, they compared the results with N-isotope measurements.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Once their analytical method was verified, Barak et al. proceeded to gather additional data specific to cranberries.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This included studying diurnal variations in nutrient uptake, examining the correlation between ammonium uptake and proton efflux, and exploring the relationship between ion concentration and uptake.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These findings highlight the potential of aeroponics not only as a valuable research tool for studying nutrient uptake but also as a means to monitor plant health and optimize crop cultivation in closed environments.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Atomization at pressures exceeding 65 pounds per square inch (450 kPa) increases the bioavailability of nutrients.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Consequently, nutrient strength must be significantly reduced to prevent leaf and root burn.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] It's worth noting the large water droplets in the photo on the right, which indicate that the feed cycle may be too long or the pause cycle too short.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Both scenarios discourage lateral root growth and root hair development.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Optimal results are achieved when feed cycles are as short as possible, with roots remaining slightly damp but never excessively dry.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] A typical feed/pause cycle is less than 2 seconds of feeding followed by approximately 1.5–2 minutes of pause, maintained continuously.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, when an accumulator system is incorporated, cycle times can be further reduced to less than approximately 1 second of feeding and around 1 minute of pause.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Shortly after its development, aeroponics emerged as a valuable research tool, providing researchers with a non-invasive method to examine developing roots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This innovative technology expanded the possibilities for conducting experiments by offering a larger number of parameters and a wider range of experimental conditions.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The precise control over root zone moisture levels and water delivery makes aeroponics particularly well-suited for studying water stress.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Hubick evaluated aeroponics as a means to consistently produce plants with minimal water stress, which can be utilized in drought or flood physiology experiments.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics are a better choice when it comes to investigating root morphology.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The absence of aggregates enables researchers to easily access the entire, intact root structure without causing damage that may occur when removing roots from soils or aggregates.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] It has been observed that aeroponics yields more natural root systems compared to hydroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] An *aeroponic system* refers to the collection of hardware and components designed to support plant growth in an air culture.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] An *aeroponic greenhouse* is a controlled environment structure made of glass or plastic, equipped with the necessary tools to cultivate plants in an air/mist environment.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In most low-pressure aeroponic gardens, the plant roots are suspended above a reservoir of nutrient solution or inside a channel connected to a reservoir.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] A low-pressure pump is used to deliver the nutrient solution either through jets or ultrasonic transducers, and the excess solution then drips or drains back into the reservoir.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, as plants mature in these units, it is common for certain sections of the root systems to become dry, which hinders proper nutrient uptake.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These units typically lack the necessary features to purify the nutrient solution and effectively remove inconsistencies, debris, and harmful pathogens.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Due to their cost constraints, such units are often more suitable for small-scale benchtop growing and for demonstrating the principles of aeroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] High-pressure aeroponic techniques, which employ mist generation through high-pressure pump(s), are commonly employed in the cultivation of high value crops and plant specimens.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The benefits of using this method in horticulture can compensate for the higher setup costs involved.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] High-pressure aeroponic systems incorporate advanced technologies for air and water purification, nutrient sterilization, the utilization of low-mass polymers, and pressurized nutrient delivery systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These features enhance the efficiency and effectiveness of the aeroponic setup.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Commercial aeroponic systems comprise high-pressure device hardware along with biological systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The biological systems matrix incorporates various enhancements aimed at extending plant life and promoting crop maturation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These commercial aeroponic systems, including the high-pressure devices, are primarily utilized for cultivating high-value crops, enabling multiple crop rotations on a continuous commercial scale.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Advanced commercial systems go a step further by incorporating data gathering, monitoring, analytical feedback, and internet connectivity to various subsystems, enhancing overall efficiency and productivity.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Artsikhovski published an article titled "On Air Plant Cultures" in the journal "Experienced Agronomy." In this article, he introduced his method of conducting physiological studies on root systems by spraying various substances in the surrounding air, which is now known as the aeroponics method.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Artsikhovski designed the first aeroponic systems and demonstrated their effectiveness for plant cultivation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Carter conducted pioneering research on air culture growing and described a method for growing plants in water vapor to facilitate root examination.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Since 2006, aeroponics has been widely used in agriculture worldwide.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Klotz made an important discovery by misting citrus plants, which facilitated his research on diseases affecting citrus and avocado roots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Trowel successfully grew apple trees using a spray culture technique.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Went coined the term "aeroponics" to describe the air-growing process.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] He grew coffee plants and tomatoes with air-suspended roots, nourishing them through the application of a nutrient mist to the root section.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The first commercially available aeroponic apparatus was manufactured and brought to market by GTi in 1983.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] At that time, it was named the *Genesis Machine*, inspired by the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] GTi's device featured an open-loop water-driven system controlled by a microchip.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] It delivered a high-pressure hydro-atomized nutrient spray within an aeroponic chamber.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The *Genesis Machine* was designed to be connected to a water faucet and an electrical outlet, providing the necessary resources for operation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponic culturing has brought about a revolution in cloning (vegetative propagation) of plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] It has made the propagation of numerous plants, previously considered difficult or impossible, much easier through stem cuttings in aeroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Delicate hardwoods and cacti, which were sensitive to bacterial infections when propagated through cuttings, can now be successfully propagated in aeroponic systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The success of propagation in aeroponics can be attributed to the highly aerated environment around the roots, promoting root hair development (Soffer and Burger, 1988), as well as enhanced root and overall growth due to nutrient supply through the aeroponic system (Santos and Fisher, 2009).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, the absence of rooting media reduces the risk of root diseases (Mehandru et al., 2014).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics plays a crucial role in propagating plants that have low success rates in vegetative propagation, plants with significant medicinal uses, high-demand plants, and in creating new cultivars of specific plant species.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] For instance, Leptadenia reticulata, an important medicinal plant with low reproductive rates through both seeds and cuttings, has found easier propagation through aeroponics (Mehandru et al., 2014).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics has also contributed to the availability of elm trees, including Ulmus Americana cultivars, which were severely affected by Dutch elm disease (Oakes et al., 2012).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics serves as a more advantageous alternative to the traditional method of using overhead misters (Peterson et al., 2018).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] It boasts a higher success rate compared to overhead misters, which have drawbacks such as the need for large volumes of water, potential unsanitary conditions, uneven misting coverage, and possible leaching of foliar nutrients (Peterson et al., 2018).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In essence, cloning has become easier with the use of aeroponic apparatus, as it initiates faster and cleaner root development through a sterile, nutrient-rich, highly oxygenated, and moist environment (Hughes, 1983).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics has made significant advancements in tissue culture technology, enabling faster plant cloning and reducing the labor-intensive steps associated with traditional tissue culture techniques.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] One of the notable benefits of aeroponics is its ability to eliminate the need for stage I and stage II plantings into soil, which has been a challenge for tissue culture growers.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In tissue culture, plants are initially planted in sterile media (stage I) and then transferred to sterile soil (stage II) before eventually being transplanted to field soil.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This entire process is not only labor-intensive but also prone to disease, infection, and failure.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] By utilizing aeroponics, growers can directly clone and transplant air-rooted plants into field soil.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The aeroponic roots are more resistant to wilting, leaf loss, and transplant shock compared to traditional methods like hydroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Moreover, air-rooted plants tend to be healthier and less susceptible to pathogen infections.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, it is important to maintain the root chamber's relative humidity (RH) below 70 °F (21 °C) to prevent the development of issues like fungus gnats, algae, and anaerobic bacteria.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The efforts of GTi in developing an all-plastic aeroponic method and apparatus controlled by a microprocessor have ushered in a new era of artificial life support for plants, allowing them to grow naturally without the use of soil or traditional hydroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In fact, GTi obtained a patent for their innovative aeroponic system in 1985.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics has gained recognition as a time- and cost-saving technique.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The economic application of aeroponics in agriculture is under development in the 21st century.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1985, GTi unveiled the second generation of aeroponics hardware, known as the "Genesis Growing System".
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This new apparatus represented a significant advancement in aeroponics technology as it introduced a closed-loop system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The Genesis Growing System utilized recycled effluent, which was precisely controlled by a microprocessor.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] With this innovation, aeroponics expanded its capabilities to include supporting seed germination, making GTi's system the world's first plant and harvest aeroponic system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] It is worth noting that many of these early open-loop and closed-loop aeroponic systems continue to operate successfully to this day.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics made its transition from laboratories to the commercial cultivation sector.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1966, Bruce Briggs, a pioneer in commercial aeroponics, successfully induced roots on hardwood cuttings through air-rooting.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] He discovered that air-rooted cuttings were more robust and hardened compared to those formed in soil, and concluded that air-rooting was a sound principle.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Briggs also found that air-rooted trees could be transplanted to soil without experiencing transplant shock, which is often observed in hydroponic transplants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1982, Isaac Nir in Israel developed a patent for an aeroponic apparatus that utilized compressed low-pressure air to deliver a nutrient solution to suspended plants held by a perforated layer of plastic foam material styrofoam inside large metal containers.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1976, British researcher John Prewer conducted a series of aeroponic experiments in the UK, where lettuces were grown from seed to maturity in 22 days using polyethylene film tubes.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The fog droplets used in these experiments were generated by equipment supplied by Mee Industries of California.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In collaboration with John Prewer, a commercial grower named Kings Nurseries on the Isle of Wight used a different design of aeroponics system in 1984 to grow strawberry plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The strawberries flourished, yielding a bountiful crop that was highly appreciated by customers, especially the elderly, who valued the cleanliness, quality, and flavor of the fruit, as well as the convenience of picking it without stooping.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1983, Richard Stoner filed a patent for the first microprocessor interface designed to deliver tap water and nutrients into an enclosed aeroponic chamber made of plastic.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Stoner subsequently established several companies dedicated to researching and advancing aeroponic hardware, interfaces, biocontrols, and components for commercial aeroponic crop production.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Stoner's company, Genesis Technology Inc, played a pioneering role in manufacturing, marketing, and applying large-scale closed-loop aeroponic systems in greenhouses for commercial crop production.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In the 1990s, General Hydroponics [Europe] (GHE) attempted to introduce aeroponics to the hobby hydroponics market and introduced the Aerogarden system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Although the Aerogarden did not meet the criteria of "true" aeroponics as it produced droplets instead of a fine mist, it created a demand for aeroponic growing in the hobby market.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The distinction between mist aeroponics and droplet aeroponics became blurred in the eyes of many.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, a UK firm called Nutriculture conducted trials of true mist aeroponics, which showed positive results compared to traditional growing techniques like Nutrient Film Technique (NFT) and Ebb & Flood.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1986, Stoner achieved a significant milestone by becoming the first person to successfully market fresh aeroponically grown food to a national grocery chain.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] His accomplishment garnered attention, and he was invited for an interview on NPR, where he highlighted the significance of aeroponics in terms of water conservation, both in modern agriculture and even in space exploration.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Plants had their first encounters with Earth's orbit back in 1960 during two separate missions, namely Sputnik 4 and Discoverer 17 (for a comprehensive review of plant growth in space during the first 30 years, refer to Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The Sputnik 4 mission involved carrying seeds of wheat, pea, maize, spring onion, and *Nigella damascena*, while *Chlorella pyrenoidosa* cells were taken into orbit on the Discoverer 17 mission.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Following these early endeavors, plant experiments were conducted on various missions involving Bangladesh, China, and joint Soviet-American efforts, including Biosatellite II, Skylab 3 and 4, Apollo-Soyuz, Sputnik, Vostok, and Zond.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Initial research findings shed light on how low gravity affected the orientation of roots and shoots (Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Subsequent research delved into investigating the impact of low gravity on plants at different levels, such as organismic, cellular, and subcellular.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] At the organismic level, several species including pine, oat, mung bean, lettuce, cress, and *Arabidopsis thaliana* exhibited decreased seedling, root, and shoot growth under low gravity conditions.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, lettuce grown on the Cosmos mission showed the opposite effect, displaying enhanced growth in space (Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Mineral uptake in plants grown in space was also found to be affected.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] For instance, peas grown in space demonstrated increased levels of phosphorus and potassium, while the divalent cations calcium, magnesium, manganese, zinc, and iron exhibited decreased levels (Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1996, Richard Stoner's research on organic disease control (ODC) received funding from NASA.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The goal was to develop a natural liquid biocontrol solution for closed-loop hydroponic systems that could prevent plant diseases and increase yields without the need for pesticides.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] By 1997, NASA conducted biocontrol experiments with Stoner's ODC solution.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The experiments took place using BioServe Space Technologies' GAP technology, which consisted of miniature growth chambers.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Bean seeds were treated with the ODC solution in triplicate experiments conducted aboard the MIR space station, at the Kennedy Space Center, and at Colorado State University under total darkness conditions to eliminate light as a variable.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The focus of the NASA experiment was solely on studying the benefits of the biocontrol.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Results from NASA's enclosed environment bean experiments on the MIR space station and shuttle confirmed that ODC promoted increased germination rates, better sprouting, enhanced growth, and activated natural plant disease mechanisms.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Although initially developed for NASA, ODC is not limited to space applications.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Soil and hydroponics growers can also incorporate ODC into their planting techniques, as it complies with USDA NOP standards for organic farming.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] One notable example of ODC's expansion in agriculture is its application in the cannabis industry.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The ODC product line has been developed specifically for emerging agricultural crops like cannabis.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The active ingredients in the ODC cannabis line include the original chitosan ingredient at a concentration of 0.25%, as well as 0.28% colloidal nitrogen and 0.05% calcium.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In order to enhance the resilience of hydroponic and aeroponic systems against plant diseases and reduce reliance on chemical additives, NASA explores the integration of environmental biocontrols into the design of these systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The Advanced Plant Habitat (APA), deployed on the International Space Station (ISS) since 2018, exemplifies this approach.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Equipped with over 180 sensors, the APA optimizes plant growth and health while decreasing the need for chemical additive biocontrols.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The sensors monitor various environmental factors, including lighting intensity, spectrum, and photoperiod, temperature, CO2 levels, relative humidity, irrigation, as well as plant-derived ethylene and volatile organic compound (VOC) scrubbing.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, the APA features leaf and root zone temperature sensors, root zone moisture sensors, and oxygen concentration meters.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These environmental controls serve two main purposes in inhibiting plant diseases.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Firstly, they maintain environmental conditions that directly hinder the growth of diseases, fungi, and pests.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] By carefully regulating factors like temperature and humidity, the risk of infections, such as botrytis in leaves, is reduced as the environment becomes less conducive to disease proliferation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Secondly, these controls create conditions that promote the plant's natural disease prevention mechanisms, indirectly inhibiting the effects of plant diseases.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] For instance, experiments with peppers conducted under blue light conditions have shown increased resilience to powdery mildew.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1998, Stoner received funding from NASA to develop a high-performance aeroponic system suitable for use on Earth as well as in space.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Through his research, Stoner demonstrated significant increases in growth rates of lettuce plants cultivated in aeroponic systems compared to other cultivation techniques.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] NASA subsequently adopted many of the aeroponic advancements developed by Stoner.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Research efforts have focused on identifying and developing technologies for rapid plant growth in different gravitational environments.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Low-gravity environments present challenges such as efficient delivery of water and nutrients to plants, as well as the recovery of waste products.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Food production in space also requires addressing issues like water management, minimizing water usage, and reducing system weight.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, future food production on planetary bodies like the Moon and Mars will involve dealing with reduced gravity environments.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Given the varying fluid dynamics at different levels of gravity, optimizing nutrient delivery systems has been a major focus in developing plant growth systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Various nutrient delivery methods are currently employed, both on Earth and in low-gravity environments.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Substrate-dependent methods include traditional soil cultivation, zeoponics, agar, and nutrient-loaded ion exchange resins.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In addition to substrate-dependent approaches, non-soil methods have been developed, including the nutrient film technique, ebb and flow, aeroponics, and others.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Hydroponic systems, with their high nutrient solution throughput, can achieve rapid plant growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, this necessitates large volumes of water and significant recycling of the solution, which poses challenges for controlling solutions in microgravity conditions.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponic systems use hydro-atomized sprays to deliver nutrients, resulting in minimal water usage, enhanced root oxygenation, and excellent plant growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The nutrient solution throughput of aeroponic systems is higher compared to other systems designed for low-gravity environments.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics eliminates the need for substrates and reduces the quantity of waste material that must be managed by other life support systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] By removing the substrate requirement, planting and harvesting processes are simplified, automation becomes easier, the weight and volume of expendable materials are reduced, and a potential pathway for pathogen transmission is eliminated.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These advantages highlight the potential of aeroponic production in microgravity environments and its efficiency in food production for outer space.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 1999, NASA allocated funding to support the development of an inflatable low-mass aeroponic system (AIS) for high-performance food production in both space and on Earth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The AIS is a self-contained and self-supporting system designed to deliver nutrients and mist to plant roots in an aeroponic environment.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Its inflatable structure offers the advantage of being lightweight and can be deflated to occupy less volume during transportation and storage.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This current version of AIS represents an improvement over previous designs that utilized rigid structures, which tend to be more costly to manufacture and transport.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] On Earth, the cost of materials and transportation can pose challenges to the economic viability of aeroponic systems for commercial growers.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] However, these challenges become even more pronounced when considering the limitations imposed by payload mass for space transportation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] To overcome these limitations, NASA has developed specialized materials capable of withstanding the harsh space environment for inflatable habitats and structures.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These materials, similar to aramid fibers, are currently being utilized in the development of expandable habitats by Bigelow Aerospace.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Successful tests have been conducted in space with one of Bigelow's Expandable Activity Modules, demonstrating the feasibility of such inflatable structures in the space environment.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics possesses numerous characteristics that contribute to its effectiveness and efficiency as a method of plant cultivation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Plants grown using aeroponics spend 99.98% of their time in the air, with only 0.02% in direct contact with hydro-atomized nutrient solution.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This minimal contact with water allows the roots to efficiently capture oxygen.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, the hydro-atomized mist plays a significant role in effectively oxygenating the roots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] A comparison between aeroponics and Nutrient Film Technique (NFT) reveals that aeroponics has a lower nutrient throughput of 1.5 milliliters per minute, in contrast to NFT's 1 liter per minute.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The reduced volume of nutrient throughput in aeroponics leads to a reduction in the overall amount of nutrients required for plant development.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Another advantage of the reduced throughput, particularly relevant for space applications, is the decreased water volume used.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This reduction in water volume not only lightens the weight needed to sustain plant growth but also reduces the buffer volume.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, the volume of effluent produced by the plants is minimized in aeroponics, resulting in a reduced amount of water that requires treatment for reuse.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The use of relatively small solution volumes in aeroponics, combined with the limited exposure of roots to the hydro-atomized mist, minimizes root-to-root contact and reduces the spread of pathogens among plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics provides greater control over the environment surrounding the root zone compared to other plant growth systems like hydroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In aeroponics, the plant roots are not continuously surrounded by any medium.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics offers the flexibility to administer various nutrient solutions to the root zone without the need to flush out previous solutions or matrices.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This high level of control is particularly valuable for studying the impact of different nutrient regimens on specific plant species.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Moreover, aeroponics enables a wider range of growth conditions compared to other nutrient delivery systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] For instance, the interval and duration of nutrient sprays can be finely adjusted to meet the specific requirements of a plant species.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This means that the aboveground tissue can experience a different environment from that of the roots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The design of an aeroponic system enables convenient handling of plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This is due to the individual separation of plants and their suspension in the air, free from any matrix that could entrap the roots.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] As a result, harvesting each plant becomes a straightforward task.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Similarly, removing any infected plant is easily done without the risk of uprooting or contaminating nearby plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponic systems offer cost-effective advantages compared to other systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The reduced volume of solution throughput, as mentioned earlier, translates to lower water and nutrient requirements in the system.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, the elimination of substrates and the need for many moving parts contribute to cost savings.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics offers a solution to minimize the negative impact of pathogens in seed stocks.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] As previously mentioned, the separation of plants and the absence of a shared growth matrix contribute to this advantage.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Moreover, aeroponics provides an enclosed and controlled environment, making it an ideal system for growing pathogen-free seed stocks.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The enclosed growth chamber, combined with the isolation of plants from each other, serves to prevent initial contamination from external pathogens and limits the spread of any existing pathogens among plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponics represents a significant advancement in artificial life support for plants, offering benefits such as non-damaging plant support, efficient seed germination, precise environmental control, and unrestricted growth.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In comparison to traditional agricultural techniques like hydroponics and drip irrigation, which have been in use for decades, aeroponics provides notable improvements in plant cultivation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Contemporary aeroponic techniques have been extensively researched at NASA's BioServe Space Technologies ( Archived 2018-06-15 at the Wayback Machine ) located on the campus of the University of Colorado in Boulder, Colorado.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This research center focuses on the development and commercialization of aeroponic systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Additionally, scientists at Ames Research Center have conducted research on enclosed loop systems, investigating methods for growing food crops in low-gravity environments to support future space colonization efforts.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 2000, Stoner was granted a patent for his organic disease control biocontrol technology, which enables pesticide-free cultivation in aeroponic systems.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] A notable milestone in aeroponics occurred in 2004 when Ed Harwood, the founder of AeroFarms, invented an innovative aeroponic system that utilizes micro fleece cloth to grow lettuces.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] AeroFarms, leveraging Harwood's patented aeroponic technology, currently operates the largest indoor vertical farm in the world based on its annual growing capacity in Newark, New Jersey.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This state-of-the-art farm employs aeroponic technology to produce and distribute up to two million pounds of pesticide-free leafy greens each year.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Aeroponic bio-pharming is an innovative approach used to cultivate pharmaceutical medicines within plants.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This technology provides complete containment, ensuring that effluents and by-products of biopharma crops are confined within a closed-loop facility.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Neil Reese of South Dakota State University conducted GMO research using aeroponics to grow genetically modified corn.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Reese considers it a significant achievement to successfully grow corn in an aeroponic system for bio-massing.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Previous attempts at growing various types of corn using hydroponics had been unsuccessful.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Through the implementation of advanced aeroponics techniques, Dr.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Reese was able to harvest mature ears of genetically modified corn while effectively containing the corn pollen and spent effluent water, thus preventing their release into the environment.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This containment ensures that the surrounding environment remains free from GMO contamination.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Reese emphasizes that aeroponics offers the potential for economically viable bio-pharming practices, making it a promising avenue for pharmaceutical production.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] In 2006, the Institute of Biotechnology at Vietnam National University of Agriculture, in collaboration with Stoner, established a postgraduate doctoral program focused on aeroponics.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The Agrobiotech Research Center, led by Professor Nguyen Quang Thach, is utilizing aeroponic laboratories to advance Vietnam's minituber potato production for certified seed potato cultivation.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] This development holds significant historical importance as it marks the first time a nation has specifically prioritized aeroponics to bolster its agricultural sector, promote economic growth in farming, meet rising demands, improve food quality, and increase overall production.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] "We have shown that aeroponics, more than any other form of agricultural technology, will significantly improve Vietnam's potato production.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] We have very little tillable land, aeroponics makes complete economic sense to us," affirmed Thach.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The integration of aeroponics in Vietnamese agriculture begins with the production of low-cost, certified disease-free organic minitubers.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] These minitubers then serve as a local supply for farmers engaged in field plantings of seed potatoes and commercial potatoes.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] The adoption of aeroponics will benefit potato farmers by providing them with disease-free seed potatoes grown without the use of pesticides.
[src:agriculture/aeroponics] Importantly, it will also reduce their operational costs and increase their yields, according to Thach.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Studies of business growth and performance in farming have found that successful agricultural businesses are cost-efficient internally and operate in favourable economic, political, and physical-organic environments.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] They are able to expand and make profits, improve the productivity of land, labor, and capital, and keep their costs down to ensure market price competitiveness.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It encompasses a broader spectrum through the agribusiness system which includes input supplies, value-addition, marketing, entrepreneurship, microfinancing, and agricultural extension.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In some countries like the Philippines, creation and management of agribusiness enterprises require consultation with registered agriculturists above a certain level of operations, capitalization, land area, or number of animals in the farm.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The word "agribusiness" is a portmanteau of the words *agriculture* and *business.* The earliest known use of the word was in the Volume 155 of the Canadian Almanac & Directory published in 1847.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Their book argued against the New Deal programs of then U.S.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] President Franklin Roosevelt as it led to the increase in agricultural prices.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Davis and Goldberg favored corporate-driven agriculture or large-scale farming to revolutionize the agriculture sector, lessening the dependency on state power and politics.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] They explained in the book that vertically integrated firms within the agricultural value chains have the ability to control prices and where they are distributed.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Goldberg then assisted in the establishment of the first undergraduate program in agribusiness in 1966 at the UP College of Agriculture in Los Baños, Philippines as Bachelor of Science in Agriculture major in Agribusiness.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The program was initially a joint undertaking with the UP College of Business Administration in Diliman, Quezon City until 1975.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Drilon of the University of the Philippines then published the book "*Agribusiness Management Resource Materials*" (1971) which would be the foundation of current agribusiness programs around the world.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In 1973, Drilon and Goldberg further expanded the concept of agribusiness to include support organizations such as governments, research institutions, schools, financial institutions, and cooperatives within the integrated Agribusiness System.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Shultz II (2005) of Loyola University Chicago reframed the definition of agribusiness to emphasize its lack of focus on farm production but towards market centricity and innovative approach to serve consumers worldwide.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Boland defined the unique economic characteristics of agribusiness supply chains from industrial manufacturing and service supply chains.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In 2017, noting the rise of genetic engineering and biotechnology in agriculture, Goldberg further expanded the definition of agribusiness which covers all the interdependent aspects of the food system including medicine, nutrition, and health.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] He also emphasized the responsibility of agribusiness to be environmentally and socially conscious towards sustainability.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Some agribusinesses have adopted the triple bottom line framework such as aligning for fair trade, organic, good agricultural practices, and B-corporation certifications towards the concept of social entrepreneurship.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The term value chain was first popularized in a book published in 1985 by Michael Porter, who used it to illustrate how companies could achieve what he called “competitive advantage” by adding value within their organization.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Subsequently, the term was adopted for agricultural development purposes and has now become very much in vogue among those working in this field, with most bilateral and multilateral aid organisations using it to guide their development interventions.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] At the heart of the agricultural value chain concept is the idea of actors connected along a chain producing and delivering goods to consumers through a sequence of activities.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] However, this “vertical” chain cannot function in isolation and an important aspect of the value chain approach is that it also considers “horizontal” impacts on the chain, such as input and finance provision, extension support and the general enabling environment.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The approach has been found useful, particularly by donors, in that it has resulted in a consideration of all those factors impacting on the ability of farmers to access markets profitably, leading to a broader range of chain interventions.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It is used both for upgrading existing chains and for donors to identify market opportunities for small farmers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] An agricultural supply store or agrocenter is an agriculturally-oriented shop where one sells agricultural supplies — inputs required for agricultural production such as pesticides, feed and fertilizers .
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Sometimes these stores are organized as cooperatives, where store customers aggregate their resources to purchase agricultural inputs.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural supply and the stores that provide it are part of the larger Agribusiness industry.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] A farmworker or farmhand, is someone employed for labor in agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In labor law, the term "farmworker" is sometimes used more narrowly, applying only to a hired worker involved in agricultural production, including harvesting.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural work varies widely depending on context, degree of mechanization and crop.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Low wages for farmworkers have been associated with farmworker shortages and delayed adoption of agricultural technology.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural labor is often affected by the human health impacts of environmental issues related to agriculture, such as health effects of pesticides or exposure to other health challenges such as valley fever.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] To address these environmental concerns and marginal working conditions, many labor rights, economic justice and environmental justice movements have been organized or supported by farmworkers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Irrigation in agriculture is the practice of applying controlled amounts of water to land to help grow crops, landscape plants, and lawns.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Irrigation has been a key aspect of agriculture for over 5,000 years and has been developed by many cultures worldwide.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Irrigation helps to grow crops, maintain landscapes, and revegetate disturbed soils in dry areas and during times of below-average rainfall.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In addition to these uses, irrigation is also employed to protect crops from frost, suppress weed growth in grain fields, and prevent soil consolidation.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It is also used to cool livestock, reduce dust, dispose of sewage, and support mining operations.Drainage, which involves the removal of surface and sub-surface water from a given location, is often studied in conjunction with irrigation.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Irrigation and drainage improvements are not necessarily mutually exclusive.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Often both may be required together to assure sustained high-level production of crops.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] For a discussion of the role of drainage practices in agriculture .
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Several irrigation methods differ in how water is supplied to plants.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Surface irrigation, also known as gravity irrigation, is the oldest form of irrigation and has been in use for thousands of years.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In sprinkler irrigation, water is piped to one or more central locations within the field and distributed by overhead high-pressure water devices.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation is a system that distributes water under low pressure through a piped network and applies it as a small discharge to each plant.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation uses less pressure and water flow than sprinkler irrigation.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Drip irrigation delivers water directly to the root zone of plants.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Subirrigation has been used in field crops in areas with high water tables for many years.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It involves artificially raising the water table to moisten the soil below the root zone of plants.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Irrigation water can come from groundwater (extracted from springs or by using wells), from surface water (withdrawn from rivers, lakes or reservoirs) or from non-conventional sources like treated wastewater, desalinated water, drainage water, or fog collection.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Irrigation can be supplementary to rainfall, which is common in many parts of the world as rainfed agriculture, or it can be full irrigation, where crops rarely rely on any contribution from rainfall.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Full irrigation is less common and occurs only in arid landscapes with very low rainfall or when crops are grown in semi-arid areas outside the rainy season.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The environmental effects of irrigation relate to the changes in quantity and quality of soil and water as a result of irrigation and the subsequent effects on natural and social conditions in river basins and downstream of an irrigation scheme.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The effects stem from altered hydrological conditions resulting from the installation and operation of the irrigation scheme.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Amongst these problems is the depletion of underground aquifers through overdrafting.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Soil can be over-irrigated due to poor distribution uniformity or management wastes water, chemicals, and may lead to water pollution.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Over-irrigation can cause deep drainage from rising water tables, which can lead to irrigation salinity problems, requiring watertable control through some form of subsurface land drainage.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Seed companies produce and sell seeds for flowers, fruits and vegetables to commercial growers and amateur gardeners.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The production of seed is a multibillion-dollar global business, which uses growing facilities and growing locations worldwide.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] While most of the seed is produced by large specialist growers, large amounts are also produced by small growers who produce only one to a few crop types.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The larger companies supply seed both to commercial resellers and wholesalers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The resellers and wholesalers sell to vegetable and fruit growers, and to companies who package seed into packets and sell them on to the amateur gardener.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Most seed companies or resellers that sell to retail produce a catalog, for seed to be sown the following spring, that is generally published during early winter.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] These catalogs are eagerly awaited by the amateur gardener, as during winter months there is little that can be done in the garden so this time can be spent planning the following year’s gardening.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The largest collection of nursery and seed trade catalogs in the U.S. is held at the National Agricultural Library where the earliest catalogs date from the late 18th century, with most published from the 1890s to the present.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Seed companies produce a huge range of seeds from highly developed F1 hybrids to open pollinated wild species.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] They have extensive research facilities to produce plants with genetic materials that result in improved uniformity and appeal.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] These qualities might include disease resistance, higher yields, dwarf habit and vibrant or new colors.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] These improvements are often closely guarded to protect them from being utilized by other producers, thus plant cultivars are often sold under the company's own name and protected by international laws from being grown for seed production by others.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Along with the growth in the allotment movement, and the increasing popularity of gardening, there have emerged many small independent seed companies.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Many of these are active in seed conservation and encouraging diversity.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] They often offer organic and open pollinated varieties of seeds as opposed to hybrids.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Many of these varieties are heirloom varieties.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The use of old varieties maintains diversity in the horticultural gene pool.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It may be more appropriate for amateur gardeners to use older (heirloom) varieties as the modern seed types are often the same as those grown by commercial producers, and so characteristics which are useful to them (e.g. vegetables ripening at the same time) may be unsuited to home growing.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] A fertilizer or fertiliser is any material of natural or synthetic origin that is applied to soil or to plant tissues to supply plant nutrients.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Fertilizers may be distinct from liming materials or other non-nutrient soil amendments.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Many sources of fertilizer exist, both natural and industrially produced.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] For most modern agricultural practices, fertilization focuses on three main macronutrients: nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) with occasional addition of supplements like rock flour for micronutrients.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Farmers apply these fertilizers in a variety of ways: through dry or pelletized or liquid application processes, using large agricultural equipment, or hand-tool methods.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Historically, fertilization came from natural or organic sources: compost, animal manure, human manure, harvested minerals, crop rotations, and byproducts of human-nature industries (e.g. fish processing waste, or bloodmeal from animal slaughter).
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] However, starting in the 19th century, after innovations in plant nutrition following Justus von Liebig's discoveries, an agricultural industry developed around synthetically created agrochemical fertilizers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] This transition was important in transforming the global food system towards larger-scale industrial agriculture with large crop yields in monocultures.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The invention of Haber process for producing ammonia for nitrogen in the 20th century combined with amplified chemical production capacity created during World War II led to a boom in using nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In the latter half of the 20th century, increased use of nitrogen fertilizers (800% increase between 1961 and 2019) has been a crucial component of the increased productivity of conventional food systems as part of the so-called "Green Revolution".
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Fertilizers, especially when applied excessively, can have environmental consequences such as water pollution and eutrophication due to nutrient runoff.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Additionally, the chemical process for creating the fertilizers results in byproducts, including carbon and other emissions.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In some cases contamination and pollution of soil result by accumulation of heavy metals contained in some fertilizers collected through mining.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Sustainable agricultural practices, such as reduced tillage and planting buffer strips, can minimize these adverse environmental effects.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] A farm (also called an agricultural holding) is an area of land that is devoted primarily to agricultural processes with the primary objective of producing food and other crops; it is the basic facility in food production.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The name is used for specialized units such as arable farms, vegetable farms, fruit farms, dairy, pig and poultry farms, and land used for the production of natural fiber, biofuel, and other biobased products.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It includes ranches, feedlots, orchards, plantations and estates, smallholdings, and hobby farms, and includes the farmhouse and agricultural buildings as well as the land.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In modern times, the term has been extended to include such industrial operations as wind farms and fish farms, both of which can operate on land or at sea.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] There are about 570 million farms in the world, most of which are small and family-operated.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Small farms with a land area of fewer than 2 hectares operate on about 12% of the world's agricultural land, and family farms comprise about 75% of the world's agricultural land.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Modern farms in developed countries are highly mechanized.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In the United States, livestock may be raised on rangeland and finished in feedlots, and the mechanization of crop production has brought about a great decrease in the number of agricultural workers needed.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In Europe, traditional family farms are giving way to larger production units.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In Australia, some farms are very large because the land is unable to support a high stocking density of livestock because of climatic conditions.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In less developed countries, small farms are the norm, and the majority of rural residents are subsistence farmers, feeding their families and selling any surplus products in the local market.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] An agricultural engineer is an engineer with an agriculture background.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural engineers make the engineering designs and plans in an agricultural project, usually in partnership with an agriculturist who is more proficient in farming and agricultural science.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Primary food processing turns agricultural products, such as raw wheat kernels or livestock, into something that can eventually be eaten.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] This category includes ingredients that are produced by ancient processes such as drying, threshing, winnowing and milling grain, shelling nuts, and butchering animals for meat.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It also includes deboning and cutting meat, freezing and smoking fish and meat, extracting and filtering oils, canning food, preserving food through food irradiation, and candling eggs, as well as homogenizing and pasteurizing milk.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Contamination and spoilage problems in primary food processing can lead to significant public health threats, as the resulting foods are used so widely.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] However, many forms of processing contribute to improved food safety and longer shelf life before the food spoils.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Commercial food processing uses control systems such as hazard analysis and critical control points (HACCP) and failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA) to reduce the risk of harm.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Secondary food processing is the everyday process of creating food from ingredients that are ready to use.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Baking bread, regardless of whether it is made at home, in a small bakery, or in a large factory, is an example of secondary food processing.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Fermenting fish and making wine, beer, and other alcoholic products are traditional forms of secondary food processing.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Sausages are a common form of secondary processed meat, formed by comminution (grinding) of meat that has already undergone primary processing.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Most of the secondary food processing methods known to humankind are commonly described as cooking methods.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural marketing covers the services involved in moving an agricultural product from the farm to the consumer.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] These services involve the planning, organizing, directing and handling of agricultural produce in such a way as to satisfy farmers, intermediaries and consumers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Numerous interconnected activities are involved in doing this, such as planning production, growing and harvesting, grading, packing and packaging, transport, storage, agro- and food processing, provision of market information, distribution, advertising and sale.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Effectively, the term encompasses the entire range of supply chain operations for agricultural products, whether conducted through *ad hoc* sales or through a more integrated chain, such as one involving contract farming.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] A farmers' market (or farmers market according to the AP stylebook, also farmer's market in the Cambridge Dictionary) is a physical retail marketplace intended to sell foods directly by farmers to consumers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Farmers' markets may be indoors or outdoors and typically consist of booths, tables or stands where farmers sell their produce, live animals and plants, and sometimes prepared foods and beverages.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Farmers' markets exist in many countries worldwide and reflect the local culture and economy.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The size of the market may be just a few stalls or it may be as large as several city blocks.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Due to their nature, they tend to be less rigidly regulated than retail produce shops.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] They are distinguished from public markets, which are generally housed in permanent structures, open year-round, and offer a variety of non-farmer/non-producer vendors, packaged foods and non-food products.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural extension is the application of scientific research and new knowledge to agricultural practices through farmer education.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The field of 'extension' now encompasses a wider range of communication and learning activities organized for rural people by educators from different disciplines, including agriculture, agricultural marketing, health, and business studies.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Extension practitioners can be found throughout the world, usually working for government agencies.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] They are represented by several professional organizations, networks and extension journals.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural extension agencies in developing countries receive large amounts of support from international development organizations such as the World Bank and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] An agricultural cooperative, also known as a farmers' co-op, is a producer cooperative in which farmers pool their resources in certain areas of activities.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural production cooperatives include collective farms in former socialist countries, the kibbutzim in Israel, collectively-governed community shared agriculture, Longo Maï cooperatives in Costa Rica, France, and some other countries, CPAs in Cuba, and Nicaraguan production cooperatives.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In Southeast Asian developing countries such as Vietnam, agricultural cooperatives remain to play an important role in economic and social activities in rural areas, although they have relied mainly on government subsidies .
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Notable examples of agricultural cooperatives include Dairy Farmers Of America, the largest dairy company in the US, Amul, the largest food product marketing organization in India, and Zen-Noah, a federation of agricultural cooperatives that handles 70% of the sales of chemical fertilizers in Japan.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agricultural cooperatives are owned and democratically controlled by their members.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The governance structure can vary between the different types, but in general members elect representatives to a board of directors and contribute to organizational decision making through a democratic voting process.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) is a specialized agency of the United Nations that leads international efforts to defeat hunger and improve nutrition and food security.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Its Latin motto, *fiat panis*, translates to "let there be bread".
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It was founded on 16 October 1945 in Quebec City, Canada.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The FAO comprises 194 members, including 193 countries and one member organization, the European Union (EU).
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Its headquarters is in Rome, Italy, and it maintains regional and field offices worldwide, operating in over 130 countries.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It helps governments and development agencies coordinate their activities to improve and develop agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and land and water resources.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It also conducts research, provides technical assistance to projects, operates educational and training programs, and collects agricultural output, production, and development data.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The FAO is governed by a biennial conference representing each member country and the EU, which elects a 49-member executive council.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] of China, serves as the chief administrative officer.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Various committees govern matters such as finance, programs, agriculture, and fisheries.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Obverse: Young woman with braid facing left.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Reverse: Cow nursing calf, face value & date.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] An agriculturist, agriculturalist, agrologist, or agronomist (abbreviated as agr.) is a professional in the science, practice, and management of agriculture and agribusiness.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] It is a regulated profession in Canada, Pakistan, India, Japan, the Philippines, the United States, and the European Union.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Other names used to designate the profession include agricultural scientist, agricultural manager, agricultural planner, agriculture researcher, or agriculture policy maker.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The primary role of agriculturists are in leading agricultural projects and programs, usually in agribusiness planning or research for the benefit of farms, food, and agribusiness-related organizations.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agriculturists usually are designated in the government as public agriculturists serving as agriculture policymakers or technical advisors for policy making.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Preparation of technical engineering designs and construction for agriculture meanwhile are reserved for agricultural engineers.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agriculturists may pursue environmental planning and focus on agricultural and rural planning.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Studies of agribusiness often come from the academic fields of agricultural economics and management studies, sometimes called agribusiness management.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] To promote more development of food economies, many government agencies support the research and publication of economic studies and reports exploring agribusiness and agribusiness practices.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Some of these studies are on foods produced for export and are derived from agencies focused on food exports.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] These agencies include the Foreign Agricultural Service (FAS) of the U.S.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Department of Agriculture, Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada (AAFC), Austrade, and New Zealand Trade and Enterprise (NZTE).
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] The Federation of International Trade Associations publishes studies and reports by FAS and AAFC, as well as other non-governmental organizations on its website.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In their book *A Concept of Agribusiness*, Ray Goldberg and John Davis provided a rigorous economic framework for the field.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] They traced a complex value-added chain that begins with the farmer's purchase of seed and livestock and ends with a product fit for the consumer's table.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] Agribusiness boundary expansion is driven by a variety of transaction costs.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] As concern over global warming intensifies, biofuels derived from crops are gaining increased public and scientific attention.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] This is driven by factors such as oil price spikes, the need for increased energy security, concern over greenhouse gas emissions from fossil fuels, and support from government subsidies.
[src:agriculture/agribusiness] In Europe and in the US, increased research and production of biofuels have been mandated by law.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] An **agricultural aircraft** is an aircraft that has been built or converted for agricultural use – usually aerial application of pesticides (crop dusting) or fertilizer (aerial topdressing); in these roles, they are referred to as "crop dusters" or "top dressers".
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Agricultural aircraft are also used for hydroseeding.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] The most common agricultural aircraft are fixed-wing – such as the Air Tractor, Cessna Ag-wagon, Gippsland GA200, Grumman Ag Cat, PZL-106 KRUK, M-18 Dromader, PAC Fletcher, Piper PA-36 Pawnee Brave, Embraer EMB 202 Ipanema, and Rockwell Thrush Commander – but helicopters are also used.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Generally, agricultural aircraft have piston or turboprop engines.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] The only known exception is the Polish PZL M-15 Belphegor which has a jet engine.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Crop dusting with insecticides began in the 1920s in the United States.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] The first widely used agricultural aircraft were converted war-surplus biplanes, such as the De Havilland Tiger Moth and Stearman.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] After more effective insecticides and fungicides were developed in the 1940s, and aerial topdressing was developed by government research in New Zealand, purpose-built agricultural fixed-wing aircraft became common.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] In the US and Europe, agricultural aircraft are typically small, simple, and rugged.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Most have spraying systems attached to the trailing edges of their wings, and pumps are usually driven by wind turbines.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] All tend to be of simple, rugged STOL design.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Sometimes a ram air turbine is used as an auxiliary power source for the pumping machinery instead of taking power directly from the engine (because this can be installed without any modifications of the airplane's mechanical systems).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] In places where dedicated use as an agricultural aircraft is uneconomic, utility types such as the Antonov An-2 biplane and De Havilland Canada DHC-2 Beaver have been used.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] In the case of helicopters, tanks are placed on or outside the body of the aircraft, while a spray rig, extending outward to the sides, is attached well below the main rotor blades.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Hydroseeding is often done by helicopters using tanks and drop systems much like those used for aerial firefighting.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] To reduce drift of the sprayed materials, agricultural pilots attempt to fly just above the crops being treated.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Fields are often surrounded by obstacles such as trees, telephone lines, and farm buildings.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Purpose-built agricultural airplanes have strengthened cockpits to protect the pilot if an accident occurs.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] Aerial spraying has been controversial since the 1960s, due to environmental concerns about pesticide drift (raised for example by Rachel Carson's book *Silent Spring*).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-aircraft] It is now often subject to restrictions, for example spraying pesticide is generally banned in Sweden, although exceptions can be made such as for an area plagued by mosquitoes during summer.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Farmers have manipulated plants and animals through selective breeding for decades of thousands of years in order to create desired traits.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] In the 20th century, a surge in technology resulted in an increase in agricultural biotechnology through the selection of traits like the increased yield, pest resistance, drought resistance, and herbicide resistance.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The first food product produced through biotechnology was sold in 1990, and by 2003, 7 million farmers were utilizing biotech crops.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] More than 85% of these farmers were located in developing countries.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Traditional crossbreeding has been used for centuries to improve crop quality and quantity.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Crossbreeding mates two sexually compatible species to create a new and special variety with the desired traits of the parents.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, the honeycrisp apple exhibits a specific texture and flavor due to the crossbreeding of its parents.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] In traditional practices, pollen from one plant is placed on the female part of another, which leads to a hybrid that contains genetic information from both parent plants.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Plant breeders select the plants with the traits they're looking to pass on and continue to breed those plants.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Note that crossbreeding can only be utilized within the same or closely related species.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Mutations can occur randomly in the DNA of any organism.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] In order to create variety within crops, scientists can randomly induce mutations within plants.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Mutagenesis uses radioactivity to induce random mutations in the hopes of stumbling upon the desired trait.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Scientists can use mutating chemicals such as ethyl methanesulfonate, or radioactivity to create random mutations within the DNA.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Atomic gardens are used to mutate crops.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] A radioactive core is located in the center of a circular garden and raised out of the ground to radiate the surrounding crops, generating mutations within a certain radius.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Mutagenesis through radiation was the process used to produce ruby red grapefruits.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Polyploidy can be induced to modify the number of chromosomes in a crop in order to influence its fertility or size.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Usually, organisms have two sets of chromosomes, otherwise known as a diploidy.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] However, either naturally or through the use of chemicals, that number of chromosomes can change, resulting in fertility changes or size modification within the crop.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Seedless watermelons are created in this manner; a 4-set chromosome watermelon is crossed with a 2-set chromosome watermelon to create a sterile (seedless) watermelon with three sets of chromosomes.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Protoplast fusion is the joining of cells or cell components to transfer traits between species.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, the trait of male sterility is transferred from radishes to red cabbages by protoplast fusion.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] This male sterility helps plant breeders make hybrid crops.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] RNA interference (RNAIi) is the process in which a cell's RNA to protein mechanism is turned down or off in order to suppress genes.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] This method of genetic modification works by interfering with messenger RNA to stop the synthesis of proteins, effectively silencing a gene.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Transgenics involves the insertion of one piece of DNA into another organism's DNA in order to introduce new genes into the original organism.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] This addition of genes into an organism's genetic material creates a new variety with desired traits.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The DNA must be prepared and packaged in a test tube and then inserted into the new organism.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] New genetic information can be inserted with gene guns/biolistics.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] An example of a gene gun transgenic is the rainbow papaya, which is modified with a gene that gives it resistance to the papaya ringspot virus.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Genome editing is the use of an enzyme system to modify the DNA directly within the cell.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Genome editing is used to develop herbicide resistant canola to help farmers control weeds.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Agricultural biotechnology has been used to improve the nutritional content of a variety of crops in an effort to meet the needs of an increasing population.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Genetic engineering can produce crops with a higher concentration of vitamins.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, golden rice contains three genes that allow plants to produce compounds that are converted to vitamin A in the human body.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] This nutritionally improved rice is designed to combat the world's leading cause of blindness—vitamin A deficiency.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Similarly, the Banana 21 project has worked to improve the nutrition in bananas to combat micronutrient deficiencies in Uganda.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] By genetically modifying bananas to contain vitamin A and iron, Banana 21 has helped foster a solution to micronutrient deficiencies through the vessel of a staple food and major starch source in Africa.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Additionally, crops can be engineered to reduce toxicity or to produce varieties with removed allergens.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] One highly sought after trait is insect resistance.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] This trait increases a crop's resistance to pests and allows for a higher yield.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] An example of this trait are crops that are genetically engineered to make insecticidal proteins originally discovered in (*Bacillus thuringiensis*).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Bacillus thuringiensis is a bacterium that produces insect repelling proteins that are non-harmful to humans.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The genes responsible for this insect resistance have been isolated and introduced into many crops.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Bt corn and cotton are now commonplace, and cowpeas, sunflower, soybeans, tomatoes, tobacco, walnut, sugar cane, and rice are all being studied in relation to Bt.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Weeds have proven to be an issue for farmers for thousands of years; they compete for soil nutrients, water, and sunlight and prove deadly to crops.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Biotechnology has offered a solution in the form of herbicide tolerance.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Chemical herbicides are sprayed directly on plants in order to kill weeds and therefore competition, and herbicide resistant crops have to the opportunity to flourish.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Often, crops are afflicted by disease spread through insects (like aphids).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Spreading disease among crop plants is incredibly difficult to control and was previously only managed by completely removing the affected crop.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The field of agricultural biotechnology offers a solution through genetically engineering virus resistance.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Developing GE disease-resistant crops now include cassava, maize, and sweet potato.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Agricultural biotechnology can also provide a solution for plants in extreme temperature conditions.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] In order to maximize yield and prevent crop death, genes can be engineered that help to regulate cold and heat tolerance.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, tobacco plants have been genetically modified to be more tolerant to hot and cold conditions, with genes originally found in Carica papaya.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Other traits include water use efficiency, nitrogen use efficiency and salt tolerance.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Quality traits include increased nutritional or dietary value, improved food processing and storage, or the elimination of toxins and allergens in crop plants.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Currently, only a small number of genetically modified crops are available for purchase and consumption in the United States.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The USDA has approved soybeans, corn, canola, sugar beets, papaya, squash, alfalfa, cotton, apples, and potatoes.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] GMO apples (arctic apples) are non-browning apples and eliminate the need for anti-browning treatments, reduce food waste, and bring out flavor.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The production of Bt cotton has skyrocketed in India, with 10 million hectares planted for the first time in 2011, resulting in a 50% insecticide application reduction.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] In 2014, Indian and Chinese farmers planted more than 15 million hectares of Bt cotton.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] Agricultural biotechnology regulation in the US falls under three main government agencies: The Department of Agriculture (USDA), the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The USDA must approve the release of any new GMOs, EPA controls the regulation of insecticide, and the FDA evaluates the safety of a particular crop sent to market.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] On average, it takes nearly 13 years and $130 million of research and development for a genetically modified organism to come to market.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The regulation process takes up to 8 years in the United States.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] The safety of GMOs has become a topic of debate worldwide, but scientific articles are being conducted to test the safety of consuming GMOs in addition to the FDA's work.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-biotechnology] In one such article, it was concluded that Bt rice did not adversely affect digestion and did not induce horizontal gene transfer.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] An **agricultural cooperative**, also known as a **farmers' co-op**, is a producer cooperative in which farmers pool their resources in certain areas of activities.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] During the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries in certain areas of Greece, back then, under Ottoman rule, a particular form of cooperative organization was developed.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Networks of adjacent rural communities were organized as a local production system designed to produce specific agricultural or craft products which were then destined for international markets.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Derived from the Byzantine guilds, they were enabling better control of the production and tax collection by the Ottoman administration.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] One of the first cooperatives was the Rochdale Society, formed in 1844 in Rochdale, England.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The Society's first enterprise was a retail store, but it very soon also established a corn mill.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The first agricultural cooperatives were created also in Europe in the second half of the nineteenth century.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] They spread later to North America and the other continents.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] They have become one of the tools of agricultural development in emerging countries.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Farmers also cooperated to form mutual farm insurance societies.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] They were created in the same periods, with the initial purpose of offering farm loans.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Some became universal banks such as Crédit Agricole or Rabobank.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Cooperatives as a form of business organization are distinct from the more common investor-owned firms (IOFs).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Both are organized as corporations, but IOFs pursue profit maximization objectives, whereas cooperatives strive to maximize the benefits they generate for their members (which usually involves zero-profit operation).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The former situations are characterized in economic theory as market failure or missing services motive.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The latter drive the creation of cooperatives as a competitive yardstick or as a means of allowing farmers to build countervailing market power to oppose the IOFs.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The concept of competitive yardstick implies that farmers, faced with an unsatisfactory performance by IOFs, may form a cooperative firm whose purpose is to force the IOFs, through competition, to improve their service to farmers.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] A practical motivation for the creation of agricultural cooperatives is related to the ability of farmers to pool production and/or resources.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] In many situations within agriculture, it is simply too expensive for farmers to manufacture products or undertake a service.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Cooperatives provide a method for farmers to join in an 'association', through which a group of farmers can acquire a better outcome, typically financial, than by going alone.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] This approach is aligned to the concept of economies of scale and can also be related as a form of economic synergy, where "two or more agents working together to produce a result not obtainable by any of the agents independently".
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] While economic benefits are a strong driver for forming cooperatives, they are not the only consideration.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Similar economic advantages can also be achieved through other organizational forms, such as IOFs.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] A key advantage of the cooperative model for farmers is that they retain governance over the association, ensuring that ownership and control remain with the members.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] This structure means that profit distributions—whether through dividends or patronage rebates—are shared exclusively among farmer-members, rather than external shareholders as in IOFs.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural cooperatives play a critical role in rural socio-economic development, food security, and poverty alleviation, particularly in regions where agriculture is the main source of employment and income.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] These cooperatives provide smallholder farmers with access to resources, education, tools, and markets that might otherwise be inaccessible.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] By organizing into producer cooperatives, farmers can also increase their resilience to economic and environmental shocks.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] These organizations help build the capacity of smallholders to adapt to challenges in ways that reduce vulnerability and enhance long-term sustainability.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Some studies suggest that membership in a producer organization is more strongly correlated with improved farm output or income than other interventions, such as technical training, certification, or credit alone.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] In agriculture, there are broadly three types of cooperatives: a manufacturing/marketing cooperative, a purchasing/supply cooperative, and a service cooperative.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural marketing cooperatives are cooperative businesses owned by farmers, that market, process, package, and distribute members' agricultural products.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] By pooling production, marketing cooperatives enable farmers to increase bargaining power and participate in markets that would be difficult for individual farmers to enter.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Marketing cooperatives may also provide value added processing and other services to increase benefits to the members.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural supply cooperatives aggregate purchases, storage, and distribution of farm inputs for their members.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] By taking advantage of volume discounts and utilizing other economies of scale, supply cooperatives bring down the cost of the inputs that the members purchase from the cooperative compared with direct purchases from commercial suppliers.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Supply cooperatives provide inputs required for agricultural production, including seeds, fertilizers, chemicals, fuel, and farm machinery.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Some supply cooperatives operate machinery pools that provide mechanical field services (e.g., plowing, harvesting) to their members.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural service cooperatives provide members with services that support agricultural production.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] These services might include product transportation, storage, credit, electricity, technical assistance, and veterinary care.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Similar to supply cooperatives, service cooperatives pool members’ resources to improve access to affordable, reliable, and high-quality services that individual producers may not be able to afford on their own.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural cooperatives are governed by their farmer members through a democratically elected board of directors.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The board establishes the cooperative's strategic direction and oversees the hired management.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Hired management is responsible for the day to day operations.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Agricultural supply cooperatives have historically played a very important role in American agricultural history.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Supply cooperatives allow farmers to collectively purchase inputs such as seed, feed, fertilizer, fuel, livestock, and farm equipment.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Department of Agriculture (USDA), agricultural cooperatives reported a balance sheet of approximately $125.6 billion USD in 2024.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Although consolidation within the agricultural sector has reduced the number of cooperatives in recent years, supply cooperatives continue to provide access to quality and accessible agricultural inputs for producers.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Current examples include Grange Cooperative, founded in Oregon in 1939, and Southern States Cooperative, founded in Virginia in 1923.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Both cooperatives help farmers obtain quality seed, and other agricultural inputs catered to the needs of farmers in their respective regions.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] New Zealand has a strong history of agricultural cooperatives, dating back to the late 19th century.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The first was the small Otago Peninsula Co-operative Cheese Factory Co.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Ltd, started in 1871 at Highcliff on the Otago Peninsula.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] With active support by the New Zealand government, and small cooperatives being suitable in isolated areas, cooperatives quickly began to dominate the industry.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] By 1905, dairy cooperatives were the main organisational structure in the industry.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] In the 1920s–'30s, there were around 500 co-operative dairy companies compared to less than 70 that were privately owned.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] However, after World War II, with the advent of improved transportation, processing technologies and energy systems, a trend to merge dairy cooperatives occurred.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] By the late 1990s, there were two major cooperatives: the Waikato-based New Zealand Dairy Group and the Taranaki-based Kiwi Co-operative Dairies.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] In 2001 these two cooperatives, together with the New Zealand Dairy Board, merged to form Fonterra.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] This mega-merger was supported by the New Zealand Government as part of broader dairy industry deregulation, which allowed other companies to directly export dairy products.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Two smaller cooperatives did not join Fonterra, preferring to remain independent – the Morrinsville-based Tatua Dairy Company and Westland Milk Products on the West Coast of the South Island.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The other main agricultural co-operatives in New Zealand are in the meat and fertiliser industries.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The meat industry, which has struggled at times, has proposed various mergers similar to the creation of Fonterra; however, these have failed to gain the necessary member support.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] In Canada, the most important cooperatives of this kind were the wheat pools.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] These farmer-owned cooperatives bought and transported grain throughout Western Canada.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] They replaced the earlier privately and often foreign-owned grain buyers and came to dominate the market in the post-war period.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] By the 1990s, most had demutualized (privatized), and several mergers occurred.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Now all the former wheat pools are part of the Viterra corporation.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The Amazon region of Ecuador is known for producing world-renowned cacao beans.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] In the Napo region 850 Kichwa families have come together with help from American biologist, Judy Logback, to form an agricultural marketing cooperatives, Kallari Association.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] This cooperative has helped increase benefits for the families involved as well as to protect and defend their Kichwa culture and the Amazon rainforest.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] In India, there are networks of cooperatives at the local, regional, state and national levels that assist in agricultural marketing.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The commodities that are mostly handled are food grains, jute, cotton, sugar, milk and nuts.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Dairy farming based on the Anand Pattern, with a single marketing cooperative, is India's largest self-sustaining industry and its largest rural employment provider.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Successful implementation of the Anand model has made India the world's largest milk producer.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Small-scale farmers with a few heads of milch cattle deposit milk into the village union's collection points twice daily, and the milk is then processed at district unions.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] After this, it is marketed by the state cooperative federation nationally under the Amul brand name, India's largest food brand.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Under this model, three-fourths of the price paid by the primarily urban consumers goes into the hands of millions of small dairy farmers.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Production of sugar from sugarcane mostly takes place at cooperative sugar cane mills owned by local farmers.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] The shareholders include all farmers, small and large, supplying sugarcane to the mill.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Over the last sixty years, the local sugar mills have played a crucial part in encouraging rural political participation and as a stepping stone for aspiring politicians.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] This is particularly true in the state of Maharashtra where a large number of politicians belonging to the Congress party or NCP had ties to sugar cooperatives from their respective local areas.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Mismanagement and manipulation of the cooperative principles have made a number of these operations inefficient.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] By pooling production, marketing cooperatives allow farmers to market their products collectively, access transportation infrastructure, storage and participate in larger markets that would be inaccessible if they were selling individually.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] To meet the needs of their members, marketing cooperatives often provide additional services including processing, packaging, logistics, quality control, and market research.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] According to the USDA, there were 830 marketing cooperatives operating in the United States in 2024.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] Dairy cooperatives are one of the most significant agricultural marketing cooperatives in the United States.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] These cooperatives market milk on behalf of their members, operate processing facilities, and help farmers manage price fluctuations in the dairy industry.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-cooperative] According to the USDA, dairy cooperatives marketed approximately 167 billion pounds of milk in 2017, representing 77.8 percent of all milk marketed in the by the nation's farmers.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Economics has been defined as the study of resource allocation under scarcity.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Agricultural economics, or the application of economic methods to optimize the decisions made by agricultural producers, grew to prominence around the turn of the 20th century.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] The field of agricultural economics can be traced back to works on land economics.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Henry Charles Taylor was the greatest contributor in this period, with the establishment of the Department of Agricultural Economics at the University of Wisconsin in 1909.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Another contributor, 1979 Nobel Economics Prize winner Theodore Schultz, was among the first to examine development economics as a problem related directly to agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Schultz was also instrumental in establishing econometrics as a tool for use in analyzing agricultural economics empirically; he noted in his landmark 1956 article that agricultural supply analysis is rooted in "shifting sand", implying that it was and is simply not being done correctly.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] The farm sector is frequently cited as a prime example of the perfect competition economic paradigm.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] In Asia, the Faculty of Agricultural Economics was established in September 1919 in Hokkaido Imperial University, Japan, as Tokyo Imperial University's School of Agriculture started a faculty on agricultural economics in its second department of agricultural science.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] In the Philippines, agricultural economics was offered first by the University of the Philippines Los Baños Department of Agricultural Economics in 1919.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] With regard to natural resources, agricultural economists have developed quantitative tools for improving land management, preventing erosion, managing pests, protecting biodiversity, and preventing livestock diseases.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] While at one time, the field of agricultural economics was focused primarily on farm-level issues, in recent years agricultural economists have studied diverse topics related to the economics of food consumption.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] In addition to economists' long-standing emphasis on the effects of prices and incomes, researchers in this field have studied how information and quality attributes influence consumer behavior.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Agricultural economics research has addressed diminishing returns in agricultural production, as well as farmers' costs and supply responses.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Much research has applied economic theory to farm-level decisions.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Studies of risk and decision-making under uncertainty have real-world applications to crop insurance policies and to understanding how farmers in developing countries make choices about technology adoption.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] These topics are important for understanding prospects for producing sufficient food for a growing world population, subject to new resource and environmental challenges such as water scarcity and global climate change.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Development economics is broadly concerned with the improvement of living conditions in low-income countries, and the improvement of economic performance in low-income settings.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Many agricultural economists are interested in the food systems of developing economies, the linkages between agriculture and nutrition, and the ways in which agriculture interact with other domains, such as the natural environment.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] The International Association of Agricultural Economists (IAAE) is a worldwide professional association, which holds its major conference every three years.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] The association publishes the journal *Agricultural Economics*.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] There also is a European Association of Agricultural Economists (EAAE), an African Association of Agricultural Economists (AAAE) and an Australian Agricultural and Resource Economics Society.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Substantial work in agricultural economics internationally is conducted by the International Food Policy Research Institute.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Many countries have their own societies.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] In the United States, for example, the primary professional association is the Agricultural & Applied Economics Association (AAEA), which holds its own annual conference and also co-sponsors the annual meetings of the Allied Social Sciences Association (ASSA).
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] The AAEA publishes the *American Journal of Agricultural Economics* and *Applied Economic Perspectives and Policy*.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] In the United Kingdom the Agricultural Economics Society dates back to 1926.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] It too has an annual residential conference.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] It publishes the *Journal of Agricultural Economics* and, with the European Association of Agricultural Economists, *EuroChoices*.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Graduates from agricultural and applied economics departments find jobs in many sectors of the economy: agricultural management, agribusiness, agricultural marketing, education, the financial sector, government, natural resource and environmental management, real estate, and public relations.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] Careers in agricultural economics require at least a bachelor's degree, and research careers in the field require graduate-level training; see Masters in Agricultural Economics.
[src:agriculture/agricultural-economics] A 2011 study by the Georgetown Center on Education and the Workforce rated agricultural economics tied for 8th out of 171 fields in terms of employability.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] As of 2021, small farms, of which the vast majority are one hectare (about 2.5 acres) or smaller, produce about one-third of the world's food.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Moreover, five of every six farms in the world consist of fewer than 2 hectares (4.9 acres) and take up only around 12% of all agricultural land.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In terms of total land use, large farms are dominant.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] While only 1% of all farms globally are greater than 50 hectares (120 acres), they encompass more than 70% of the world's farmland.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Further, nearly 40% of all global agricultural land is found on farms larger than 1,000 hectares (2,500 acres).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Farms and farming greatly influence rural economics and greatly shape rural society, affecting both the direct agricultural workforce and broader businesses that support the farms and farming populations.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The major agricultural products can be broadly grouped into foods, fibers, fuels, and raw materials (such as rubber and timber).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Food classes include cereals (grains), vegetables, fruits, cooking oils, meat, milk, eggs, and fungi.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global agricultural production amounts to approximately 11 billion tonnes of food, 32 million tonnes of natural fibers and 4 billion m3 of wood.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] However, around 14% of the world's food is lost from production before reaching the retail level.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Modern agronomy, plant breeding, agrochemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers, and technological developments have sharply increased crop yields, but also contributed to ecological and environmental damage.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Selective breeding and modern practices in animal husbandry have similarly increased the output of meat, but have raised concerns about animal welfare and environmental damage.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Environmental issues include contributions to climate change, depletion of aquifers, deforestation, antibiotic resistance, and other agricultural pollution.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is both a cause of and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation, and climate change, all of which can cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms are widely used, although some countries ban them.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The word *agriculture* is a late Middle English adaptation of Latin *agricultūra*, from *ager* 'field' and *cultūra* 'cultivation' or 'growing'.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture is defined with varying scopes, in its broadest sense using natural resources to "produce commodities which maintain life, including food, fiber, forest products, horticultural crops, and their related services".
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Thus defined, it includes arable farming, horticulture, animal husbandry and forestry, but horticulture and forestry are in practice often excluded.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] It may also be broadly decomposed into **plant agriculture**, which concerns the cultivation of useful plants, and **animal agriculture**, the production of agricultural animals.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] While agriculture usually refers to human activities, other species have been cultivating crops for up to 60 million years, such as some ant (see agriculture in ants), termite and beetle.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The development of agriculture enabled the human population to grow many times larger than could be sustained by hunting and gathering.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture began independently in different parts of the globe, and included a diverse range of taxa, in at least 11 separate centers of origin.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Wild grains were collected and eaten from at least 105,000 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Paleolithic Levant, 23,000 years ago, cereals cultivation of emmer, barley, and oats has been observed near the sea of Galilee.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Rice was domesticated in China between 11,500 and 6200 BC with the earliest known cultivation from 5700 BC, followed by mung, soy and azuki beans.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sheep were domesticated in Mesopotamia between 13,000 and 11,000 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cattle were domesticated from the wild aurochs in the areas of modern Turkey and Pakistan some 10,500 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pig production emerged in Eurasia, including Europe, East Asia and Southwest Asia, where wild boar were first domesticated about 10,500 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Andes of South America, the potato was domesticated between 10,000 and 7,000 years ago, along with beans, coca, llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sugarcane and some root vegetables were domesticated in New Guinea around 9,000 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sorghum was domesticated in the Sahel region of Africa by 7,000 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 5,600 years ago, and was independently domesticated in Eurasia.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In Mesoamerica, wild teosinte was bred into maize (corn) from 10,000 to 6,000 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The horse was domesticated in the Eurasian Steppes around 3500 BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Scholars have offered multiple hypotheses to explain the historical origins of agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Studies of the transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural societies indicate an initial period of intensification and increasing sedentism; examples are the Natufian culture in the Levant, and the Early Chinese Neolithic in China.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Then, wild stands that had previously been harvested started to be planted, and gradually came to be domesticated.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In Eurasia, the Sumerians started to live in villages from about 8000 BC, relying on the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and a canal system for irrigation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ploughs appear in pictographs around 3000 BC; seed-ploughs around 2300 BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Farmers grew wheat, barley, vegetables such as lentils and onions, and fruits including dates, grapes, and figs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ancient Egyptian agriculture relied on the Nile River and its seasonal flooding.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Farming started in the predynastic period at the end of the Paleolithic, after 10,000 BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Staple food crops were grains such as wheat and barley, alongside industrial crops such as flax and papyrus.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In India, wheat, barley and jujube were domesticated by 9000 BC, soon followed by sheep and goats.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cattle, sheep and goats were domesticated in Mehrgarh culture by 8000–6000 BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cotton was cultivated by the 5th–4th millennium BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Archeological evidence indicates an animal-drawn plough from 2500 BC in the Indus Valley civilization.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In China, from the 5th century BC, there was a nationwide granary system and widespread silk farming.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Water-powered grain mills were in use by the 1st century BC, followed by irrigation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] By the late 2nd century, heavy ploughs had been developed with iron ploughshares and mouldboards.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Asian rice was domesticated 8,200–13,500 years ago – depending on the molecular clock estimate that is used– on the Pearl River in southern China with a single genetic origin from the wild rice *Oryza rufipogon*.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In Greece and Rome, the major cereals were wheat, emmer, and barley, alongside vegetables including peas, beans, and olives.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sheep and goats were kept mainly for dairy products.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Americas, crops domesticated in Mesoamerica (apart from teosinte) include squash, beans, and cacao.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cocoa was domesticated by the Mayo Chinchipe of the upper Amazon around 3000 BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The turkey was probably domesticated in Mexico or the American Southwest.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Aztecs developed irrigation systems, formed terraced hillsides, fertilized their soil, and developed chinampas or artificial islands.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Mayas used extensive canal and raised field systems to farm swampland from 400 BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In South America agriculture may have begun about 9000 BC with the domestication of squash (Cucurbita) and other plants.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Coca was domesticated in the Andes, as were the peanut, tomato, tobacco, and pineapple.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cotton was domesticated in Peru by 3600 BC.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Animals including llamas, alpacas, and guinea pigs were domesticated there.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In North America, the indigenous people of the East domesticated crops such as sunflower, tobacco, squash and *Chenopodium*.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Wild foods including wild rice and maple sugar were harvested.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The domesticated strawberry is a hybrid of a Chilean and a North American species, developed by breeding in Europe and North America.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The indigenous people of the Southwest and the Pacific Northwest practiced forest gardening and fire-stick farming.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The natives controlled fire on a regional scale to create a low-intensity fire ecology that sustained a low-density agriculture in loose rotation; a sort of "wild" permaculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] A system of companion planting called the Three Sisters was developed in North America.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The three crops were winter squash, maize, and climbing beans.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Indigenous Australians, long supposed to have been nomadic hunter-gatherers, practiced systematic burning, possibly to enhance natural productivity in fire-stick farming.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Scholars have pointed out that hunter-gatherers need a productive environment to support gathering without cultivation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Because the forests of New Guinea have few food plants, early humans may have used "selective burning" to increase the productivity of the wild karuka fruit trees to support the hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Gunditjmara and other groups developed eel farming and fish trapping systems from some 5,000 years ago.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] There is evidence of 'intensification' across the whole continent over that period.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In two regions of Australia, the central west coast and eastern central, early farmers cultivated yams, native millet, and bush onions, possibly in permanent settlements.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the Middle Ages, compared to the Roman period, agriculture in Western Europe became more focused on self-sufficiency.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The agricultural population under feudalism was typically organized into manors consisting of several hundred or more acres of land presided over by a lord of the manor with a Roman Catholic church and priest.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Thanks to the exchange with the Al-Andalus where the Arab Agricultural Revolution was underway, European agriculture transformed, with improved techniques and the diffusion of crop plants, including the introduction of sugar, rice, cotton and fruit trees (such as the orange).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] After 1492, the Columbian exchange brought New World crops such as maize, potatoes, tomatoes, sweet potatoes, and manioc to Europe, and Old World crops such as wheat, barley, rice, and turnips, and livestock (including horses, cattle, sheep and goats) to the Americas.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Irrigation, crop rotation, and fertilizers advanced from the 17th century with the British Agricultural Revolution, allowing global population to rise significantly.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Since 1900, agriculture in developed nations, and to a lesser extent in the developing world, has seen large rises in productivity as mechanization replaces human labor, and assisted by synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and selective breeding.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Haber-Bosch method allowed the synthesis of ammonium nitrate fertilizer on an industrial scale, greatly increasing crop yields and sustaining a further increase in global population.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pastoralism involves managing domesticated animals.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In nomadic pastoralism, herds of livestock are moved from place to place in search of pasture, fodder, and water.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced in arid and semi-arid regions of Sahara, Central Asia and some parts of India.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In shifting cultivation, a small area of forest is cleared by cutting and burning the trees.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The cleared land is used for growing crops for a few years until the soil becomes too infertile, and the area is abandoned.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Another patch of land is selected and the process is repeated.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This type of farming is practiced mainly in areas with abundant rainfall where the forest regenerates quickly.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This practice is used in Northeast India, Southeast Asia, and the Amazon Basin.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Subsistence farming is practiced to satisfy family or local needs alone, with little left over for transport elsewhere.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] It is intensively practiced in Monsoon Asia and South-East Asia.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] An estimated 2.5 billion subsistence farmers worked in 2018, cultivating about 60% of the earth's arable land.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Intensive farming is cultivation to maximize productivity, with a low fallow ratio and a high use of inputs (water, fertilizer, pesticide and automation).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] It is practiced mainly in developed countries.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] From the twentieth century onwards, intensive agriculture increased crop productivity.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] It substituted synthetic fertilizers and pesticides for labor, but caused increased water pollution, and often involved farm subsidies.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Soil degradation and diseases such as stem rust are major concerns globally; approximately 40% of the world's agricultural land is seriously degraded.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Modern agriculture has raised or encountered ecological, political, and economic issues including water pollution, biofuels, genetically modified organisms, tariffs and farm subsidies, leading to alternative approaches such as the organic movement.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Unsustainable farming practices in North America led to the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In recent years there has been a backlash against the environmental effects of conventional agriculture, resulting in the organic, regenerative, and sustainable agriculture movements.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] One of the major forces behind this movement has been the European Union, which first certified organic food in 1991 and began reform of its Common Agricultural Policy (CAP) in 2005 to phase out commodity-linked farm subsidies, also known as decoupling.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The growth of organic farming has renewed research in alternative technologies such as integrated pest management, selective breeding, and controlled-environment agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] There are concerns about the lower yield associated with organic farming and its impact on global food security.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Recent mainstream technological developments include genetically modified food.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] During the 60-year period between 1964 and 2023, most of the increase in agricultural production was achieved through intensification, while the expansion of agricultural land was limited to just 8%.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the twenty-first century, between 2001 and 2023, global agricultural area decreased by 78 million hectares (Mha) (−2%), with cropland area increasing by 78 Mha and permanent meadows and pastures decreasing by 151 Mha.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] These changes exhibit significant regional variations.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa witnessed cropland expansion of 69 Mha accompanied by 72 Mha of forest loss, while Latin America saw 25 Mha of cropland growth alongside 85 Mha of net forest area loss.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion remains the primary driver of global deforestation, accounting for nearly 90% of forest loss.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In this century, another important aspect to consider is that approximately 3.6 Mha of croplands are abandoned annually, with land degradation likely playing a significant role in these losses.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] By 2015, the agricultural output of China was the largest in the world, followed by the European Union, India and the United States.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Economists measure the total factor productivity of agriculture, according to which agriculture in the United States is roughly 1.7 times more productive than it was in 1948.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture employed 873 million people in 2021, or 27% of the global workforce, 916 million in 2023, compared with 1 027 million (or 40%) in 2000.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The share of agriculture in global GDP was stable at around 4% since 2000–2023.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Despite increases in agricultural production and productivity, between 702 and 828 million people were affected by hunger in 2021.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Food insecurity and malnutrition can be the result of conflict, climate extremes and variability and economic swings.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] It can also be caused by a country's structural characteristics such as income status and natural resource endowments as well as its political economy.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pesticide use in agriculture went up 62% between 2000 and 2021, with the Americas accounting for half the use in 2021.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The International Fund for Agricultural Development posits that an increase in smallholder agriculture may be part of the solution to concerns about food prices and overall food security, given the favorable experience of Vietnam.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture provides about one-quarter of all global employment, more than half in sub-Saharan Africa and almost 60 percent in low-income countries.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] As countries develop, other jobs have historically pulled workers away from agriculture, and labor-saving innovations increase agricultural productivity by reducing labor requirements per unit of output.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Over time, a combination of labor supply and labor demand trends have driven down the share of population employed in agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] During the 16th century in Europe, between 55 and 75% of the population was engaged in agriculture; by the 19th century, this had dropped to between 35 and 65%.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the same countries today, the figure is less than 10%.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] At the start of the 21st century, some one billion people, or over 1/3 of the available work force, were employed in agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This constitutes approximately 70% of the global employment of children, and in many countries constitutes the largest percentage of women of any industry.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The service sector overtook the agricultural sector as the largest global employer in 2007.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In many developed countries, immigrants help fill labor shortages in high-value agriculture activities that are difficult to mechanize.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Foreign farm workers from mostly Eastern Europe, North Africa and South Asia constituted around one-third of the salaried agricultural workforce in Spain, Italy, Greece and Portugal in 2013.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Around the world, women make up a large share of the population employed in agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This share is growing in all developing regions except East and Southeast Asia where women already make up about 50 percent of the agricultural workforce.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women make up 47 percent of the agricultural workforce in sub-Saharan Africa, a rate that has not changed significantly in the past few decades.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women who work in agricultural production tend to do so under highly unfavorable conditions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] They tend to be concentrated in the poorest countries, where alternative livelihoods are not available, and they maintain the intensity of their work in conditions of climate-induced weather shocks and in situations of conflict.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women are less likely to participate as entrepreneurs and independent farmers and are engaged in the production of less lucrative crops.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The gender gap in land productivity between female- and male managed farms of the same size is 24 percent.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] On average, women earn 18.4 percent less than men in wage employment in agriculture; this means that women receive 82 cents for every dollar earned by men.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Progress has been slow in closing gaps in women's access to irrigation and in ownership of livestock, too.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women in agriculture still have significantly less access than men to inputs, including improved seeds, fertilizers and mechanized equipment.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] On a positive note, the gender gap in access to mobile internet in low- and middle-income countries fell from 25 percent to 16 percent between 2017 and 2021, and the gender gap in access to bank accounts narrowed from 9 to 6 percentage points.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Women are as likely as men to adopt new technologies when the necessary enabling factors are put in place and they have equal access to complementary resources.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture, specifically farming, remains a hazardous industry, and farmers worldwide remain at high risk of work-related injuries, lung disease, noise-induced hearing loss, skin diseases, as well as certain cancers related to chemical use and prolonged sun exposure.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] On industrialized farms, injuries frequently involve the use of agricultural machinery, and a common cause of fatal agricultural injuries in developed countries is tractor rollovers.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pesticides and other chemicals used in farming can be hazardous to worker health, and workers exposed to pesticides may experience illness or have children with birth defects.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] As an industry in which families commonly share in work and live on the farm itself, entire families can be at risk for injuries, illness, and death.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ages 0–6 may be an especially vulnerable population in agriculture; common causes of fatal injuries among young farm workers include drowning, machinery and motor accidents, including with all-terrain vehicles.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Occupational fatality data from the last decade indicate that, when looking at all industries, agriculture had the leading number of work-related deaths for youth.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Within this industry, youth between the ages of 10 and 15 suffered the most non-fatal work-related injuries.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] While farming is hazardous, studies have looked at the fact that there are also many benefits to growing up and living on a farm.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The International Labor Organization considers agriculture "one of the most hazardous of all economic sectors".
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] It estimates that the annual work-related death toll among agricultural employees is at least 170,000, twice the average rate of other jobs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In addition, incidences of death, injury and illness related to agricultural activities often go unreported.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The organization has developed the Safety and Health in Agriculture Convention, 2001, which covers the range of risks in the agriculture occupation, the prevention of these risks and the role that individuals and organizations engaged in agriculture should play.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the United States, agriculture has been identified by the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health as a priority industry sector in the National Occupational Research Agenda to identify and provide intervention strategies for occupational health and safety issues.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In the European Union, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work has issued guidelines on implementing health and safety directives in agriculture, livestock farming, horticulture, and forestry.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Agricultural Safety and Health Council of America (ASHCA) also holds a yearly summit to discuss safety.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Extending over 4.8 billion ha in 2025 – the equivalent of one-third of the Earth's land surface – agriculture has a greater impact on land and water resources compared with any other economic sector.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pressure on land, soil and water resources has seriously compromised the performance and future prospects of agriculture, resulting in further loss of productive land and reduced water availability for farming and other forms of agricultural production.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural expansion drives deforestation and is one of the primary causes of the degradation of carbon-rich ecosystems such as peatlands.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] An estimated 64% of agricultural land is at risk of pesticide pollution, which damages biodiversity by destroying pollinators, harms soil microbiota and makes agrifood systems less resilient to pests, pathogens and climate change.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Accounting for 72% of global freshwater withdrawals, a figure predicted to rise further in the future, agriculture contributes to and is increasingly affected by water scarcity.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Overexploitation of groundwater and seawater intrusion in coastal aquifers is widespread, with major implications for food security.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Overall production varies by country as listed.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cropping systems vary among farms depending on the available resources and constraints; geography and climate of the farm; government policy; economic, social and political pressures; and the philosophy and culture of the farmer.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Shifting cultivation (or slash and burn) is a system in which forests are burnt, releasing nutrients to support cultivation of annual and then perennial crops for a period of several years.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Then the plot is left fallow to regrow forest, and the farmer moves to a new plot, returning after many more years (10–20).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This fallow period is shortened if population density grows, requiring the input of nutrients (fertilizer or manure) and some manual pest control.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Annual cultivation is the next phase of intensity in which there is no fallow period.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This requires even greater nutrient and pest control inputs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Further industrialization led to the use of monocultures, when one cultivar is planted on a large acreage.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Because of the low biodiversity, nutrient use is uniform and pests tend to build up, necessitating the greater use of pesticides and fertilizers.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Multiple cropping, in which several crops are grown sequentially in one year, and intercropping, when several crops are grown at the same time, are other kinds of annual cropping systems known as polycultures.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In subtropical and arid environments, the timing and extent of agriculture may be limited by rainfall, either not allowing multiple annual crops in a year, or requiring irrigation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In all of these environments perennial crops are grown (coffee, chocolate) and systems are practiced such as agroforestry.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In temperate environments, where ecosystems were predominantly grassland or prairie, highly productive annual farming is the dominant agricultural system.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Important categories of food crops include cereals, legumes, forage, fruits and vegetables.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Natural fibers include cotton, wool, hemp, silk and flax.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Specific crops are cultivated in distinct growing regions throughout the world.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Production is listed in millions of metric tons, based on FAO estimates.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Animal husbandry is the breeding and raising of animals for meat, milk, eggs, or wool, and for work and transport.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Working animals, including horses, mules, oxen, water buffalo, camels, llamas, alpacas, donkeys, and dogs, have for centuries been used to help cultivate fields, harvest crops, wrangle other animals, and transport farm products to buyers.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Livestock production systems can be defined based on feed source, as grassland-based, mixed, and landless.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] As of 2010, 30% of Earth's ice- and water-free area was used for producing livestock, with the sector employing approximately 1.3 billion people.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Between the 1960s and the 2000s, there was a significant increase in livestock production, both by numbers and by carcass weight, especially among beef, pigs and chickens, the latter of which had production increased by almost a factor of 10.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Non-meat animals, such as milk cows and egg-producing chickens, also showed significant production increases.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global cattle, sheep and goat populations are expected to continue to increase sharply through 2050.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Aquaculture or fish farming, the production of fish for human consumption in confined operations, is one of the fastest growing sectors of food production, growing at an average of 9% a year between 1975 and 2007.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] During the second half of the 20th century, producers using selective breeding focused on creating livestock breeds and crossbreeds that increased production, while mostly disregarding the need to preserve genetic diversity.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This trend has led to a significant decrease in genetic diversity and resources among livestock breeds, leading to a corresponding decrease in disease resistance and local adaptations previously found among traditional breeds.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Grassland based livestock production relies upon plant material such as shrubland, rangeland, and pastures for feeding ruminant animals.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Outside nutrient inputs may be used, however manure is returned directly to the grassland as a major nutrient source.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This system is particularly important in areas where crop production is not feasible because of climate or soil, representing 30–40 million pastoralists.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Mixed production systems use grassland, fodder crops and grain feed crops as feed for ruminant and monogastric (one stomach; mainly chickens and pigs) livestock.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Manure is typically recycled in mixed systems as a fertilizer for crops.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Landless systems rely upon feed from outside the farm, representing the de-linking of crop and livestock production found more prevalently in Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development member countries.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Synthetic fertilizers are more heavily relied upon for crop production and manure use becomes a challenge as well as a source for pollution.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Industrialized countries use these operations to produce much of the global supplies of poultry and pork.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Scientists estimate that 75% of the growth in livestock production between 2003 and 2030 will be in confined animal feeding operations, sometimes called factory farming.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Much of this growth is happening in developing countries in Asia, with much smaller amounts of growth in Africa.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some of the practices used in commercial livestock production, including the usage of growth hormones, are controversial.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Tillage is the practice of breaking up the soil with tools such as the plow or harrow to prepare for planting, for nutrient incorporation, or for pest control.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Tillage varies in intensity from conventional to no-till.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] It can improve productivity by warming the soil, incorporating fertilizer and controlling weeds, but also renders soil more prone to erosion, triggers the decomposition of organic matter releasing CO2, and reduces the abundance and diversity of soil organisms.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Pest control includes the management of weeds, insects, mites, and diseases.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Chemical (pesticides), biological (biocontrol), mechanical (tillage), and cultural practices are used.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Cultural practices include crop rotation, culling, cover crops, intercropping, composting, avoidance, and resistance.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Integrated pest management attempts to use all of these methods to keep pest populations below the number which would cause economic loss, and recommends pesticides as a last resort.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Nutrient management includes both the source of nutrient inputs for crop and livestock production, and the method of use of manure produced by livestock.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Nutrient inputs can be chemical inorganic fertilizers, manure, green manure, compost and minerals.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Crop nutrient use may also be managed using cultural techniques such as crop rotation or a fallow period.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Manure is used either by holding livestock where the feed crop is growing, such as in managed intensive rotational grazing, or by spreading either dry or liquid formulations of manure on cropland or pastures.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Water management is needed where rainfall is insufficient or variable, which occurs to some degree in most regions of the world.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some farmers use irrigation to supplement rainfall.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In other areas such as the Great Plains in the US and Canada, farmers use a fallow year to conserve soil moisture for the following year.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Recent technological innovations in precision agriculture allow for water status monitoring and automate water usage, leading to more efficient management.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agriculture represents 70% of freshwater use worldwide.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] However, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture vary significantly by income level.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In least developed countries and landlocked developing countries, water withdrawal ratios for agriculture are as high as 90 percent of total water withdrawals and about 60 percent in Small Island Developing States.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] According to 2014 report by the International Food Policy Research Institute, agricultural technologies will have the greatest impact on food production if adopted in combination with each other.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Payment for ecosystem services is a method of providing additional incentives to encourage farmers to conserve some aspects of the environment.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Measures might include paying for reforestation upstream of a city, to improve the supply of fresh water.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Different definitions exist for agricultural automation and for the variety of tools and technologies that are used to automate production.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] One view is that agricultural automation refers to autonomous navigation by robots without human intervention.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Alternatively, it is defined as the accomplishment of production tasks through mobile, autonomous, decision-making, mechatronic devices.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] However, FAO finds that these definitions do not capture all the aspects and forms of automation, such as robotic milking machines that are static, most motorized machinery that automates the performing of agricultural operations, and digital tools (e.g., sensors) that automate only diagnosis.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] FAO defines agricultural automation as the use of machinery and equipment in agricultural operations to improve their diagnosis, decision-making or performing, reducing the drudgery of agricultural work or improving the timeliness, and potentially the precision, of agricultural operations.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has involved a progressive move from manual tools to animal traction, to motorized mechanization, to digital equipment and finally, to robotics with artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Precision agriculture often employs such automation technologies.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Motorized machines are increasingly complemented, or even superseded, by new digital equipment that automates diagnosis and decision-making.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] A conventional tractor, for example, can be converted into an automated vehicle allowing it to sow a field autonomously.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Motorized mechanization has increased significantly across the world in recent years, although reliable global data with broad country coverage exist only for tractors and only up to 2009.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global automatic milking system sales have increased over recent years, but adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Measuring the overall employment impacts of agricultural automation is difficult because it requires large amounts of data tracking all the transformations and the associated reallocation of workers both upstream and downstream.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] While automation technologies reduce labor needs for the newly automated tasks, they also generate new labor demand for other tasks, such as equipment maintenance and operation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural automation can also stimulate employment by allowing producers to expand production and by creating other agrifood systems jobs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This is especially true when it happens in context of rising scarcity of rural labor, as is the case in high-income countries and many middle-income countries.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] On the other hand, if forcedly promoted, for example through government subsidies in contexts of abundant rural labor, it can lead to labor displacement and falling or stagnant wages, particularly affecting poor and low-skilled workers.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Climate change and agriculture are interrelated on a global scale.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Global warming is already affecting agriculture, with effects unevenly distributed across the world.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In a 2022 report, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change describes how human-induced warming has slowed growth of agricultural productivity over the past 50 years in mid and low latitudes.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Methane emissions have negatively impacted crop yields by increasing temperatures and surface ozone concentrations.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Warming is also negatively affecting crop and grassland quality and harvest stability.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Ocean warming has decreased sustainable yields of some wild fish populations while ocean acidification and warming have already affected farmed aquatic species.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Climate change will probably increase the risk of food insecurity for some vulnerable groups, such as the poor.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In order to meet the demands of a growing global population, agriculture needs to produce about 50% more food, feed and fibre by 2050 compared with the volumes it generated in 2012, according to estimates by the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Achieving such objectives will place additional pressure on the world's already overstretched water, land and soil resources.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Crop alteration has been practiced by humankind for thousands of years, since the beginning of civilization.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Altering crops through breeding practices changes the genetic make-up of a plant to develop crops with more beneficial characteristics for humans, for example, larger fruits or seeds, drought-tolerance, or resistance to pests.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Significant advances in plant breeding ensued after the work of geneticist Gregor Mendel.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] His work on dominant and recessive alleles, although initially largely ignored for almost 50 years, gave plant breeders a better understanding of genetics and breeding techniques.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Crop breeding includes techniques such as plant selection with desirable traits, self-pollination and cross-pollination, and molecular techniques that genetically modify the organism.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Domestication of plants has, over the centuries increased yield, improved disease resistance and drought tolerance, eased harvest and improved the taste and nutritional value of crop plants.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Careful selection and breeding have had enormous effects on the characteristics of crop plants.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Plant selection and breeding in the 1920s and 1930s improved pasture (grasses and clover) in New Zealand.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Extensive X-ray and ultraviolet induced mutagenesis efforts (i.e. primitive genetic engineering) during the 1950s produced the modern commercial varieties of grains such as wheat, corn (maize) and barley.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Green Revolution popularized the use of conventional hybridization to sharply increase yield by creating "high-yielding varieties".
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] For example, average yields of corn (maize) in the US have increased from around 2.5 tons per hectare (t/ha) (40 bushels per acre) in 1900 to about 9.4 t/ha (150 bushels per acre) in 2001.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Similarly, worldwide average wheat yields have increased from less than 1 t/ha in 1900 to more than 2.5 t/ha in 1990.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] South American average wheat yields are around 2 t/ha, African under 1 t/ha, and Egypt and Arabia up to 3.5 to 4 t/ha with irrigation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In contrast, the average wheat yield in countries such as France is over 8 t/ha.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Variations in yields are due mainly to variation in climate, genetics, and the level of intensive farming techniques (use of fertilizers, chemical pest control, and growth control to avoid lodging).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Investments into innovation for agriculture are long term.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] This is because it takes time for research to become commercialized and for technology to be adapted to meet multiple regions' needs, as well as meet national guidelines before being adopted and planted in a farmer's fields.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] For instance, it took at least 60 years from the introduction of hybrid corn technology before its adoption became widespread.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Agricultural innovation developed for the specific agroecological conditions of one region is not easily transferred and used in another region with different agroecological conditions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Instead, the innovation would have to be adapted to the specific conditions of that other region and respect its biodiversity and environmental requirements and guidelines.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some such adaptations can be seen through the steadily increasing number of plant varieties protected under the plant variety protection instrument administered by the International Union for the Protection of New Varieties of Plants (UPOV).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Genetically modified organisms (GMO) are organisms whose genetic material has been altered by genetic engineering techniques generally known as recombinant DNA technology.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Genetic engineering has expanded the genes available to breeders to use in creating desired germlines for new crops.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Increased durability, nutritional content, insect and virus resistance and herbicide tolerance are a few of the attributes bred into crops through genetic engineering.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] For some, GMO crops cause food safety and food labeling concerns.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Numerous countries have placed restrictions on the production, import or use of GMO foods and crops.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] The Biosafety Protocol, an international treaty, regulates the trade of GMOs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] There is ongoing discussion regarding the labeling of foods made from GMOs, and the EU has had GMO food labeling requirements since 1997.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] As of 2022, the United States requires food containing GMO ingredients to be labeled as well.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-resistant seeds have a gene implanted into their genome that allows the plants to tolerate exposure to herbicides, including glyphosate.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] These seeds allow the farmer to grow a crop that can be sprayed with herbicides to control weeds without harming the resistant crop.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Herbicide-tolerant crops are used by farmers worldwide.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] With the increasing use of herbicide-tolerant crops, comes an increase in the use of glyphosate-based herbicide sprays.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In some areas glyphosate resistant weeds have developed, causing farmers to switch to other herbicides.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some studies also link widespread glyphosate usage to iron deficiencies in some crops, which is both a crop production and a nutritional quality concern, with potential economic and health implications.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Other GMO crops used by growers include insect-resistant crops, which have a gene from the soil bacterium *Bacillus thuringiensis* (Bt), which produces a toxin specific to insects.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] Some believe that similar or better pest-resistance traits can be acquired through traditional breeding practices, and resistance to various pests can be gained through hybridization or cross-pollination with wild species.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p01] In some cases, wild species are the primary source of resistance traits; some tomato cultivars that have gained resistance to at least 19 diseases did so through crossing with wild populations of tomatoes.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is both a cause of environmental degradation and sensitive to environmental degradation, such as biodiversity loss, desertification, soil degradation and climate change, which cause decreases in crop yield.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is one of the most important drivers of environmental pressures, particularly habitat change, climate change, water use and toxic emissions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture is the main source of toxins released into the environment, including insecticides, especially those used on cotton.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The 2011 UNEP Green Economy report stated that agricultural operations produced some 13 percent of anthropogenic global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] This includes gases from the use of inorganic fertilizers, agro-chemical pesticides, and herbicides, as well as fossil fuel-energy inputs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture imposes multiple external costs upon society through effects such as pesticide damage to nature (especially herbicides and insecticides), nutrient runoff, excessive water usage, and loss of natural environment.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2000 assessment of agriculture in the UK determined total external costs for 1996 of £2,343 million, or £208 per hectare.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2005 analysis of these costs in the US concluded that cropland imposes approximately $5 to $16 billion ($30 to $96 per hectare), while livestock production imposes $714 million.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Both studies, which focused solely on the fiscal impacts, concluded that more should be done to internalize external costs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Neither included subsidies in their analysis, but they noted that subsidies also influence the cost of agriculture to society.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture seeks to increase yield and to reduce costs, often employing measures that cut biodiversity to very low levels.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Yield increases with inputs such as fertilizers and removal of pathogens, predators, and competitors (such as weeds).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Costs decrease with increasing scale of farm units, such as making fields larger; this means removing hedges, ditches and other areas of habitat.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Pesticides kill insects, plants and fungi.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Effective yields fall with on-farm losses, which may be caused by poor production practices during harvesting, handling, and storage.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The environmental effects of climate change show that research on pests and diseases that do not generally afflict areas is essential.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] In 2021, farmers discovered stem rust on wheat in the Champagne area of France, a disease that had previously only occurred in Morocco for 20 to 30 years.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Because of climate change, insects that used to die off over the winter are now alive and multiplying.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] A senior UN official, Henning Steinfeld, said that "Livestock are one of the most significant contributors to today's most serious environmental problems".
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Livestock production occupies 70% of all land used for agriculture, or 30% of the land surface of the planet.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] It is one of the largest sources of greenhouse gases, responsible for 18% of the world's greenhouse gas emissions as measured in CO2 equivalents.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] By comparison, all transportation emits 13.5% of the CO2.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] (This comparison later turned out to be an apples-and-oranges analogy.) It produces 65% of human-related nitrous oxide (which has 296 times the global warming potential of CO2) and 37% of all human-induced methane (which is 23 times as warming as CO2.) It also generates 64% of the ammonia emission.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Livestock expansion is cited as a key factor driving deforestation; in the Amazon basin 70% of previously forested area is now occupied by pastures and the remainder used for feed crops.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Through deforestation and land degradation, livestock is also driving reductions in biodiversity.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] A well documented phenomenon is woody plant encroachment, caused by overgrazing in rangelands.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Land transformation, the use of land to yield goods and services, is the most substantial way humans alter the Earth's ecosystems, and is the driving force causing biodiversity loss.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Estimates of the amount of land transformed by humans vary from 39 to 50%.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] It is estimated that 24% of land globally experiences land degradation, a long-term decline in ecosystem function and productivity, with cropland being disproportionately affected.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Land management is the driving factor behind degradation; 1.5 billion people rely upon the degrading land.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Degradation can be through deforestation, desertification, soil erosion, mineral depletion, acidification, or salinization.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] In 2021, the global agricultural land area was 4.79 billion hectares (ha), down 2 percent, or 0.09 billion ha compared with 2000.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Between 2000 and 2021, roughly two-thirds of agricultural land were used for permanent meadows and pastures (3.21 billion ha in 2021), which declined by 5 percent (0.17 billion ha).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] One-third of the total agricultural land was cropland (1.58 billion ha in 2021), which increased by 6 percent (0.09 billion ha).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., total agricultural land use is estimated to be 56%, and including grazing, animal agriculture constitutes around 80% of agricultural land.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Eutrophication, excessive nutrient enrichment in aquatic ecosystems resulting in algal blooms and anoxia, leads to fish kills, loss of biodiversity, and renders water unfit for drinking and other industrial uses.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Excessive fertilization and manure application to cropland, as well as high livestock stocking densities cause nutrient (mainly nitrogen and phosphorus) runoff and leaching from agricultural land.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] These nutrients are major nonpoint pollutants contributing to eutrophication of aquatic ecosystems and pollution of groundwater, with harmful effects on human populations.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Fertilizers also reduce terrestrial biodiversity by increasing competition for light, favoring those species that are able to benefit from the added nutrients.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture simultaneously is facing growing freshwater demand and precipitation anomalies (droughts, floods, and extreme rainfall and weather events) on rainfed areas fields and grazing lands.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for 70 percent of withdrawals of freshwater resources, and an estimated 41 percent of current global irrigation water use occurs at the expense of environmental flow requirements.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Within the U.S., agriculture accounts for about 80% of total water consumption, with animal agriculture making up half of agricultural consumption (around 40%).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] It is long known that aquifers in areas as diverse as northern China, the Upper Ganges and the western US are being depleted, and new research extends these problems to aquifers in Iran, Mexico and Saudi Arabia.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Increasing pressure is being placed on water resources by industry and urban areas, meaning that water scarcity is increasing and agriculture is facing the challenge of producing more food for the world's growing population with reduced water resources.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] While industrial withdrawals have declined in the past few decades and municipal withdrawals have increased only marginally since 2010, agricultural withdrawals have continued to grow at an ever faster pace.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural water usage can also cause major environmental problems, including the destruction of natural wetlands, the spread of water-borne diseases, and land degradation through salinization and waterlogging, when irrigation is performed incorrectly.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Pesticide use has increased since 1950 to 2.5 million short tons annually worldwide, yet crop loss from pests has remained relatively constant.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The World Health Organization estimated in 1992 that three million pesticide poisonings occur annually, causing 220,000 deaths.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Pesticides select for pesticide resistance in the pest population, leading to a condition termed the "pesticide treadmill" in which pest resistance warrants the development of a new pesticide.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] An alternative argument is that the way to "save the environment" and prevent famine is by using pesticides and intensive high yield farming, a view exemplified by a quote heading the Center for Global Food Issues website: 'Growing more per acre leaves more land for nature'.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] However, critics argue that a trade-off between the environment and a need for food is not inevitable, and that pesticides can replace good agronomic practices such as crop rotation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The Push–pull agricultural pest management technique involves intercropping, using plant aromas to repel pests from crops (push) and to lure them to a place from which they can then be removed (pull).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture contributes towards climate change through greenhouse gas emissions and by the conversion of non-agricultural land such as forests into agricultural land.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The agriculture, forestry and land use sector contribute between 13% and 21% of global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Emissions of nitrous oxide, methane make up over half of total greenhouse gas emission from agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Animal husbandry is a major source of greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Approximately 57% of global GHG emissions from the production of food are from the production of animal-based food while plant-based foods contribute 29% and the remaining 14% is for other utilizations.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Farmland management and land-use change represented major shares of total emissions (38% and 29%, respectively), whereas rice and beef were the largest contributing plant- and animal-based commodities (12% and 25%, respectively).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] South and Southeast Asia and South America were the largest emitters of production-based GHGs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Climate change put significant part of crops in danger already at 1.5 degrees of warming.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] While in North America, Europe and central Asia the share of endangered crops is relatively little at this level of warming, in the Middle east and North Africa region for example, close to 50% of cropland is in danger.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] With further temperature rise the risk increase in all regions, in some more, in some less.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Globally the cropland area in safe climatic zone decrease for all the major crop groups as warming exceed 1.5 degrees.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Current farming methods have resulted in over-stretched water resources, high levels of erosion and reduced soil fertility.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] There is not enough water to continue farming using current practices; therefore how water, land, and ecosystem resources are used to boost crop yields must be reconsidered.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] A solution would be to give value to ecosystems, recognizing environmental and livelihood tradeoffs, and balancing the rights of a variety of users and interests.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Inequities that result when such measures are adopted would need to be addressed, such as the reallocation of water from poor to rich, the clearing of land to make way for more productive farmland, or the preservation of a wetland system that limits fishing rights.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Technological advancements help provide farmers with tools and resources to make farming more sustainable.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Technology permits innovations like conservation tillage, a farming process which helps prevent land loss to erosion, reduces water pollution, and enhances carbon sequestration.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural automation can help address some of the challenges associated with climate change and thus facilitate adaptation efforts.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] For example, the application of digital automation technologies (e.g. in precision agriculture) can improve resource-use efficiency in conditions which are increasingly constrained for agricultural producers.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Moreover, when applied to sensing and early warning, they can help address the uncertainty and unpredictability of weather conditions associated with accelerating climate change.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Other potential sustainable practices include conservation agriculture, agroforestry, improved grazing, avoided grassland conversion, and biochar.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Current mono-crop farming practices in the United States preclude widespread adoption of sustainable practices, such as 2–3 crop rotations that incorporate grass or hay with annual crops, unless negative emission goals such as soil carbon sequestration become policy.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The food demand of Earth's projected population, with current climate change predictions, could be satisfied by improvement of agricultural methods, expansion of agricultural areas, and a sustainability-oriented consumer mindset.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Since the 1940s, agricultural productivity has increased dramatically, due largely to the increased use of energy-intensive mechanization, fertilizers and pesticides.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The vast majority of this energy input comes from fossil fuel sources.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Between the 1960s and the 1980s, the Green Revolution transformed agriculture around the globe, with world grain production increasing significantly (between 70% and 390% for wheat and 60% to 150% for rice, depending on geographic area) as world population doubled.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Heavy reliance on petrochemicals has raised concerns that oil shortages could increase costs and reduce agricultural output.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Industrialized agriculture depends on fossil fuels in two fundamental ways: direct consumption on the farm and manufacture of inputs used on the farm.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Direct consumption includes the use of lubricants and fuels to operate farm vehicles and machinery.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Indirect consumption includes the manufacture of fertilizers, pesticides, and farm machinery.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] In particular, the production of nitrogen fertilizer can account for over half of agricultural energy usage.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Together, direct and indirect consumption by US farms accounts for about 2% of the nation's energy use.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Direct and indirect energy consumption by US farms peaked in 1979, and has since gradually declined.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Food systems encompass not just agriculture but off-farm processing, packaging, transporting, marketing, consumption, and disposal of food and food-related items.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agriculture accounts for less than one-fifth of food system energy use in the US.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Plastic products are used extensively in agriculture, including to increase crop yields and improve the efficiency of water and agrichemical use.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] "Agriplastic" products include films to cover greenhouses and tunnels, mulch to cover soil (e.g. to suppress weeds, conserve water, increase soil temperature and aid fertilizer application), shade cloth, pesticide containers, seedling trays, protective mesh and irrigation tubing.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The polymers most commonly used in these products are low-density polyethylene (LPDE), linear low-density polyethylene (LLDPE), polypropylene (PP) and polyvinyl chloride (PVC).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The total amount of plastics used in agriculture is difficult to quantify.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2012 study reported that almost 6.5 million tonnes per year were consumed globally while a later study estimated that global demand in 2015 was between 7.3 million and 9 million tonnes.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Widespread use of plastic mulch and lack of systematic collection and management have led to the generation of large amounts of mulch residue.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Weathering and degradation eventually cause the mulch to fragment.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] These fragments and larger pieces of plastic accumulate in soil.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Mulch residue has been measured at levels of 50 to 260 kg per hectare in topsoil in areas where mulch use dates back more than 10 years, which confirms that mulching is a major source of both microplastic and macroplastic soil contamination.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural plastics, especially plastic films, are not easy to recycle because of high contamination levels (up to 40–50% by weight contamination by pesticides, fertilizers, soil and debris, moist vegetation, silage juice water, and UV stabilizers) and collection difficulties .
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Therefore, they are often buried or abandoned in fields and watercourses or burned.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] These disposal practices lead to soil degradation and can result in contamination of soils and leakage of microplastics into the marine environment as a result of precipitation run-off and tidal washing.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] In addition, additives in residual plastic film (such as UV and thermal stabilizers) may have deleterious effects on crop growth, soil structure, nutrient transport and salt levels.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] There is a risk that plastic mulch will deteriorate soil quality, deplete soil organic matter stocks, increase soil water repellence and emit greenhouse gases.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Microplastics released through fragmentation of agricultural plastics can absorb and concentrate contaminants capable of being passed up the trophic chain.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural economics is economics as it relates to the "production, distribution and consumption of [agricultural] goods and services".
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Combining agricultural production with general theories of marketing and business as a discipline of study began in the late 1800s, and grew significantly through the 20th century.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] In the United States, and elsewhere, food costs attributed to food processing, distribution, and agricultural marketing, sometimes referred to as the value chain, have risen while the costs attributed to farming have declined.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] This is related to the greater efficiency of farming, combined with the increased level of value addition (e.g. more highly processed products) provided by the supply chain.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Market concentration has increased in the sector as well, and although the total effect of the increased market concentration is likely increased efficiency, the changes redistribute economic surplus from producers (farmers) and consumers, and may have negative implications for rural communities.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] National government policies, such as taxation, subsidies, tariffs and others, can significantly change the economic marketplace for agricultural products.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Since at least the 1960s, a combination of trade restrictions, exchange rate policies and subsidies have affected farmers in both the developing and the developed world.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] In the 1980s, non-subsidized farmers in developing countries experienced adverse effects from national policies that created artificially low global prices for farm products.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Between the mid-1980s and the early 2000s, several international agreements limited agricultural tariffs, subsidies and other trade restrictions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] However, as of 2009, there was still a significant amount of policy-driven distortion in global agricultural product prices.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The three agricultural products with the most trade distortion were sugar, milk and rice, mainly due to taxation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Among the oilseeds, sesame had the most taxation, but overall, feed grains and oilseeds had much lower levels of taxation than livestock products.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Since the 1980s, policy-driven distortions have decreases more among livestock products than crops during the worldwide reforms in agricultural policy.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Despite this progress, certain crops, such as cotton, still see subsidies in developed countries artificially deflating global prices, causing hardship in developing countries with non-subsidized farmers.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Unprocessed commodities such as corn, soybeans, and cattle are generally graded to indicate quality, affecting the price the producer receives.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Commodities are generally reported by production quantities, such as volume, number or weight.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural science is a broad multidisciplinary field of biology that encompasses the parts of exact, natural, economic and social sciences used in the practice and understanding of agriculture.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The scientific study of agriculture began in the 18th century, when Johann Friedrich Mayer conducted experiments on the use of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulphate) as a fertilizer.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Research became more systematic when in 1843, John Lawes and Henry Gilbert began a set of long-term agronomy field experiments at Rothamsted Research Station in England; some of them, such as the Park Grass Experiment, are still running.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] In America, the Hatch Act of 1887 provided funding for what it was the first to call "agricultural science", driven by farmers' interest in fertilizers.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy is the set of government decisions and actions relating to domestic agriculture and imports of foreign agricultural products.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Governments usually implement agricultural policies with the goal of achieving a specific outcome in the domestic agricultural product markets.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agricultural policy can also touch on food quality, ensuring that the food supply is of a consistent and known quality, food security, ensuring that the food supply meets the population's needs, and conservation.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Policy programs can range from financial programs, such as subsidies, to encouraging producers to enroll in voluntary quality assurance programs.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] A 2021 report finds that globally, support to agricultural producers accounts for almost US$540 billion a year.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] This amounts to 15 percent of total agricultural production value, and is heavily biased towards measures that are leading to inefficiency, as well as are unequally distributed and harmful for the environment and human health.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Crop use in animal agriculture accounts for one form of inefficiency.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Animal agriculture's estimated land use to produce one kilocalorie or gram of protein is 50 to 100 times that of plant-based alternatives.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Furthermore, the larger the livestock, the lower the energy efficiency (kilocalories obtained relative to kilocalories the animal consumes).
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] For instance, beef's energy efficiency is estimated to be 2%.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] There are many influences on the creation of agricultural policy, including consumers, agribusiness, trade lobbies and other groups.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Agribusiness interests hold a large amount of influence over policy making, in the form of lobbying and campaign contributions.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Political action groups, including those interested in environmental issues and labor unions, also provide influence, as do lobbying organizations representing individual agricultural commodities.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) leads international efforts to defeat hunger and provides a forum for the negotiation of global agricultural regulations and agreements.
[src:agriculture/agriculture-p02] Samuel Jutzi, director of FAO's animal production and health division, states that lobbying by large corporations has stopped reforms that would improve human health and the environment.
